window.BDLS_DATA = {"manifest":{"id":"bdls","title":"BDLS — Basic Disaster Life Support","subtitle":"The Ultimate Course Reviewer","version":"1.0.0","edition":"Based on the NDLSF BDLS v4.0 curriculum","description":"A comprehensive, self-contained study reviewer for Basic Disaster Life Support. Each chapter includes a concise summary, clinical pearls, red flags, common mistakes, memory aids, decision trees, high-yield flashcards, course-style quiz questions, and realistic disaster scenarios. Built around the PRE-DISASTER and DISASTER paradigms, SALT mass-casualty triage, and the all-hazards approach for EMS providers, nurses, physicians, and public-health professionals.","icon":"tornado","color":"#c8102e","accentColor":"#1f6feb","estimatedHours":10,"difficulty":"Beginner to Intermediate","certification":"NDLSF BDLS","examLink":"https://www.ndlsf.org/bdls","audience":["EMT","AEMT","Paramedic","Nurse","Physician","Public Health Professional","Hospital Staff"],"prerequisites":["None — BDLS is an awareness-level course; clinical background helpful"],"contentTypes":["summary","flashcards","quizzes","scenarios","algorithms","tables"],"chapters":[{"id":"c01","number":1,"title":"Disaster Medicine Foundations & the PRE-DISASTER Paradigm","section":"Foundations","difficulty":"Beginner"},{"id":"c02","number":2,"title":"The DISASTER Paradigm","section":"Foundations","difficulty":"Beginner"},{"id":"c03","number":3,"title":"Incident Command & Emergency Management (ICS/NIMS)","section":"Foundations","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c04","number":4,"title":"Mass-Casualty Triage: SALT","section":"Response Core","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c05","number":5,"title":"Natural Disasters","section":"All-Hazards","difficulty":"Beginner"},{"id":"c06","number":6,"title":"Traumatic & Explosive Events","section":"All-Hazards","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c07","number":7,"title":"Chemical Events & Decontamination","section":"All-Hazards","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c08","number":8,"title":"Biological Events & Pandemics","section":"All-Hazards","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c09","number":9,"title":"Nuclear & Radiological Events","section":"All-Hazards","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c10","number":10,"title":"Surge Capacity, Psychosocial Care & Vulnerable Populations","section":"Response Core","difficulty":"Intermediate"}]},"chapters":{"c01":{"id":"c01","title":"Disaster Medicine Foundations & the PRE-DISASTER Paradigm","shortTitle":"Foundations & PRE-DISASTER","estimatedStudyTime":30,"difficulty":"Beginner","learningObjectives":["Define disaster and mass-casualty incident (MCI) from a health-system perspective.","Explain the all-hazards approach and why BDLS teaches a common lexicon.","List the four classic phases of the disaster cycle.","Describe the components of the PRE-DISASTER Paradigm for mitigation and preparedness.","Distinguish disaster response from conventional emergency care priorities.","Describe the health professional's roles before, during, and after a disaster."],"summary":[{"title":"What Makes an Event a Disaster","content":"From the health-system perspective, a disaster is an event in which the needs generated — casualties, destroyed infrastructure, displaced people — exceed the resources immediately available to meet them. The same tornado may be a routine emergency for a large trauma system and a disaster for a rural hospital. A mass-casualty incident (MCI) is an event producing more patients than local resources can manage using routine procedures. The defining feature is the imbalance between needs and resources, not the size of the event itself."},{"title":"The All-Hazards Approach","content":"Rather than writing a separate plan for every possible event, modern disaster medicine uses an all-hazards approach: a common management framework that works across natural disasters, explosions, chemical releases, epidemics, and radiological events, supplemented by hazard-specific annexes. BDLS exists to give all health professionals a shared vocabulary and knowledge base so that physicians, nurses, EMS providers, and public-health workers can integrate smoothly during a response."},{"title":"The Disaster Cycle: Four Phases","content":"Emergency management describes a continuous cycle of four phases. Mitigation: actions that reduce the impact of future events (building codes, flood barriers, immunization programs). Preparedness: planning, training, exercising, and stockpiling before an event. Response: the actions taken during and immediately after the event — the DISASTER Paradigm operates here. Recovery: restoring the community and health system to normal (or improved) function, which can take years. Health professionals have roles in every phase, not only in response."},{"title":"The PRE-DISASTER Paradigm","content":"BDLS frames what should happen before an event with the PRE-DISASTER Paradigm: Planning and practice — realistic, exercised plans at personal, facility, and community levels; Resilience — building the personal, infrastructure, and community capacity to absorb and recover from shocks; Education and training — competency-based learning such as the NDLS course family, so responders share a common playbook. Preparedness done well shrinks the gap between needs and resources when the event arrives."},{"title":"How Disaster Care Differs From Everyday Care","content":"Conventional emergency care applies maximal resources to each individual patient. In a disaster, the goal shifts to achieving the greatest good for the greatest number: triage allocates limited resources, some care is deferred, documentation is abbreviated, and providers may work outside their usual roles under an incident command structure. Recognizing and accepting this shift — before the event — is itself a preparedness skill."},{"title":"Personal and Family Preparedness","content":"A responder whose own family is unprepared is a responder who may not report for duty. Personal preparedness includes a family communication plan, a go-kit with supplies and medications, arrangements for dependents and pets, and knowledge of workplace disaster roles. Health facilities depend on their staff showing up; individual readiness is a system-level asset."}],"clinicalPearls":["A disaster is defined by the needs-versus-resources imbalance, not by the event's size or drama.","The greatest-good-for-the-greatest-number principle governs disaster care and justifies triage decisions that would be unacceptable in daily practice.","Mitigation and preparedness — the quiet phases — save more lives than heroic response.","Your family's preparedness plan is part of your hospital's surge plan: unprepared staff don't show up."],"redFlags":["Facilities that plan for only one hazard instead of using an all-hazards framework.","Plans that exist on paper but have never been exercised.","Responders self-dispatching to a scene without integration into incident command."],"commonMistakes":["Confusing a mass-casualty incident (resource strain) with any large emergency.","Treating disaster response as the only phase that matters and ignoring mitigation, preparedness, and recovery.","Assuming everyday clinical priorities (maximal care per patient) carry over unchanged into disasters."],"memoryAids":["Disaster = Demand > Resources.","The disaster cycle: Mitigate → Prepare → Respond → Recover, then repeat.","PRE-DISASTER: Planning/practice, Resilience, Education — do the work before the sirens."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Is This a Disaster (for You)?","content":"Event occurs\n  → Estimate needs: casualties, hazards, infrastructure loss, displaced people\n  → Compare with immediately available resources (staff, space, supplies, systems)\n     → Needs ≤ resources: manage as a conventional (possibly large) emergency\n     → Needs > resources: DISASTER footing\n        → Activate emergency operations / incident command\n        → Shift to greatest-good priorities and formal triage\n        → Request mutual aid and escalate through the system"}],"references":["NDLSF BDLS v4.0 — Disaster Medicine Principles and the PRE-DISASTER Paradigm","NDLSF BDLS v4.0 — All-Hazards Preparedness and the Disaster Cycle"]},"c02":{"id":"c02","title":"The DISASTER Paradigm","shortTitle":"DISASTER Paradigm","estimatedStudyTime":35,"difficulty":"Beginner","learningObjectives":["List the eight components of the DISASTER Paradigm in order.","Describe the detection questions a first-arriving responder must answer.","Explain why establishing incident command early is critical.","Apply safety-and-security thinking to self, scene, and survivors.","Describe hazard assessment, including the risk of secondary events.","Explain the support and triage/treatment components.","Describe evacuation priorities and the transition to recovery."],"summary":[{"title":"One Framework for Every Event","content":"The DISASTER Paradigm is the BDLS all-hazards response framework — a mental checklist that applies whether the event is a flood, a bombing, or an epidemic. Its components are: Detection, Incident command, Safety and security, Assess hazards, Support, Triage and treatment, Evacuation, and Recovery. It gives every responder, from any discipline, the same ordered set of priorities."},{"title":"Detection","content":"Detection asks: does this event exceed available resources — is it a disaster or MCI? Detection can be obvious (an explosion) or insidious (a slowly building epidemic, patients presenting with unusual symptoms across multiple emergency departments). The first-arriving responder estimates the number of casualties, hazards present, and resources needed, and communicates that picture early. Recognizing an event for what it is triggers everything downstream."},{"title":"Incident Command","content":"Someone must be in charge, immediately. The first trained responder on scene establishes incident command and announces it, transferring command later as more senior officers arrive. Incident command creates a single point of coordination, prevents freelancing, and connects the scene to the wider emergency-management system. Health professionals must know how to work inside this structure rather than around it."},{"title":"Safety and Security","content":"The priority order is: yourself, your team, the public/bystanders, then the patients. A responder who becomes a casualty consumes resources rather than adding them. Safety includes appropriate PPE, staging until the scene is cleared, controlling perimeters, and awareness of violence or secondary devices intended to target responders. Security also protects scarce resources — supplies, vehicles, and facilities — from being overwhelmed."},{"title":"Assess Hazards","content":"Actively search for ongoing and secondary hazards: fire, structural collapse, downed power lines, hazardous materials, rising water, aftershocks, and intentional secondary devices timed to strike responders. Hazard assessment is continuous — scenes evolve, and the assessment that was true on arrival may be false an hour later."},{"title":"Support, Triage & Treatment, Evacuation, Recovery","content":"Support: identify what resources — people, supplies, vehicles, facilities, special teams — are needed and request them early, because everything arrives with a delay. Triage and treatment: sort casualties with a standardized method (SALT) and provide the greatest good for the greatest number. Evacuation: move patients to appropriate destinations — distributing them across receiving hospitals rather than overwhelming the nearest one — and consider evacuation of populations at risk. Recovery: begins during the response, restoring systems, supporting responders and survivors, and documenting lessons learned."}],"clinicalPearls":["The DISASTER Paradigm is a checklist you run in order — detection and command come before any patient care.","The nearest hospital is not automatically the right destination; distribute casualties or you simply move the disaster indoors.","Request support early: every resource arrives after a lag, so order for the incident you will have in an hour.","Reassess hazards continuously — secondary devices and evolving scenes target the moment responders relax."],"redFlags":["Rushing to treat the first casualty seen before command, safety, and hazard assessment are addressed.","Multiple EDs seeing clusters of unusual symptoms — a detection signal for a covert biological or chemical event.","All casualties transported to the closest hospital, overwhelming it while others sit idle."],"commonMistakes":["Skipping the announcement of incident command because the scene 'seems manageable.'","Treating safety as a one-time check instead of a continuous process.","Forgetting that recovery planning starts during the response, not after it."],"memoryAids":["D-I-S-A-S-T-E-R: Detection, Incident command, Safety/security, Assess hazards, Support, Triage & treatment, Evacuation, Recovery.","Safety order: me, my team, bystanders, then patients.","Detect → Direct → Protect → Assess → Supply → Sort → Move → Restore."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"First Responder's DISASTER Sequence","content":"Arrive at possible MCI\n  → DETECTION: needs vs resources — declare MCI/disaster if exceeded\n  → INCIDENT COMMAND: establish and announce (transfer later as needed)\n  → SAFETY & SECURITY: self → team → public → patients; PPE; perimeter\n  → ASSESS HAZARDS: ongoing + secondary (devices, collapse, hazmat); reassess continuously\n  → SUPPORT: request staff, supplies, transport, special teams EARLY\n  → TRIAGE & TREATMENT: SALT; greatest good for greatest number\n  → EVACUATION: right patient, right destination — distribute, don't dump\n  → RECOVERY: begins during response; restore, support, learn"}],"references":["NDLSF BDLS v4.0 — The DISASTER Paradigm","NDLSF BDLS v4.0 — Response Principles and Scene Management"]},"c03":{"id":"c03","title":"Incident Command & Emergency Management (ICS/NIMS)","shortTitle":"ICS / NIMS","estimatedStudyTime":32,"difficulty":"Intermediate","learningObjectives":["Describe the purpose and core features of the Incident Command System (ICS).","Name the five major ICS functional sections and their responsibilities.","Explain span of control and modular expansion.","Define unified command and when it is used.","Describe NIMS and how it standardizes response across agencies.","Explain the hospital's version of ICS and the health professional's place in it."],"summary":[{"title":"Why Incident Command Exists","content":"Large events involve many agencies — fire, EMS, police, public works, hospitals, public health — that must act as one organization. The Incident Command System (ICS) is a standardized, scalable management structure that provides common terminology, clear chain of command, defined roles, and integrated communications. It prevents the classic failure of disasters: multiple groups working hard at cross purposes."},{"title":"The Five Functional Sections","content":"ICS organizes work into five functions. Command sets objectives and holds overall authority; it includes the command staff — safety officer, public information officer, and liaison officer. Operations does the tactical work: rescue, triage, treatment, transport. Planning collects information, tracks resources, and writes the incident action plan. Logistics obtains everything the response needs — supplies, facilities, food, communications. Finance/Administration tracks costs, contracts, claims, and time records. Every task in a response lives somewhere in these five functions."},{"title":"Modular, Scalable, Span of Control","content":"ICS expands and contracts with the incident: a small event may need only an incident commander, while a catastrophe activates every section with branches, divisions, and groups. The guiding rule is span of control: one supervisor should directly manage roughly three to seven people (five is the classic optimum). When a supervisor's span grows too large, the structure subdivides."},{"title":"Unified Command and Transfer of Command","content":"When an incident crosses jurisdictions or disciplines — a hazmat spill involving fire, police, EMS, and environmental agencies — unified command lets the key agencies share command decisions while maintaining a single coordinated plan and one Operations section. Command transfers formally, with a briefing, when a more qualified or designated officer assumes it; everyone is told who now commands."},{"title":"NIMS: The National Framework","content":"The National Incident Management System (NIMS) is the U.S. doctrine that standardizes incident management across all levels of government and the private sector. It incorporates ICS, defines resource typing (so a requested 'strike team' means the same thing everywhere), credentialing, mutual aid, and emergency operations centers (EOCs) that support on-scene command. For health professionals, NIMS means your hospital's system plugs into the same structure the fire service uses."},{"title":"Hospital Incident Command (HICS)","content":"Hospitals use an ICS adaptation (commonly the Hospital Incident Command System, HICS) with the same five functions applied to facility problems: bed surge, staff callback, supply shortages, evacuation. Clinicians in a disaster work within assigned roles — often defined by job action sheets — reporting through the structure rather than to their everyday supervisors. Knowing your facility's command structure before the event is a core BDLS competency."}],"clinicalPearls":["In ICS you report to your incident supervisor, not your everyday boss — one person, one supervisor.","Span of control 3–7 (optimally ~5): when a leader has more direct reports than that, the structure should subdivide.","The safety officer can halt any operation immediately — the one role with that authority besides command.","Job action sheets convert your clinical skills into a defined incident role; read yours before the disaster."],"redFlags":["Multiple agencies each running their own separate command posts for the same incident.","A supervisor directly managing 15 people — span of control has collapsed.","Staff bypassing the command structure to act on hallway instructions."],"commonMistakes":["Confusing the incident commander (on-scene authority) with the EOC (off-scene support and coordination).","Assuming ICS is only for fire services — it is designed for all disciplines including hospitals.","Forgetting the formal briefing when command transfers."],"memoryAids":["Five functions — C-O-P-L-F: Command, Operations, Planning, Logistics, Finance/Admin.","'Command thinks, Operations does, Planning tracks, Logistics gets, Finance pays.'","Span of control: one hand — about five fingers, about five reports."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Fitting Into Incident Command as a Health Professional","content":"Disaster activation announced\n  → Report to your designated check-in point (never self-dispatch)\n  → Receive assignment + job action sheet\n  → Identify YOUR incident supervisor (one person)\n  → Perform assigned role; communicate up the chain\n     → Task outside your competence? Say so — constructive refusal is safety\n     → New hazard or resource need? Report to your supervisor\n  → At shift end: formal handoff + demobilization through the system"}],"references":["NDLSF BDLS v4.0 — Incident Command and Emergency Management Systems","FEMA — NIMS and ICS doctrine (as taught in BDLS v4.0)"]},"c04":{"id":"c04","title":"Mass-Casualty Triage: SALT","shortTitle":"SALT Triage","estimatedStudyTime":40,"difficulty":"Intermediate","learningObjectives":["Explain the purpose of mass-casualty triage and how it differs from everyday triage.","Describe the SALT acronym and the global sorting step.","List the rapid lifesaving interventions permitted during SALT triage.","Assign casualties to the five SALT categories using the assessment questions.","Explain the expectant category and when it is used.","Describe re-triage and the dynamic nature of triage decisions."],"summary":[{"title":"Why a Standardized Triage Method","content":"When casualties outnumber resources, providers must decide who is treated and transported first. SALT — Sort, Assess, Lifesaving interventions, Treatment and/or transport — is the CDC-sponsored national standard taught in BDLS, designed so that responders from any agency triage the same way. Unlike daily triage (which finds the sickest patient for maximal care), mass-casualty triage rations care to produce the most survivors overall."},{"title":"Step 1 — Sort: Global Sorting by Voice and Movement","content":"SALT begins with a global sort of the whole scene using two commands. First: 'If you can hear me and need help, walk to this area' — those who walk are assessed last (lowest priority for individual assessment, often Minimal). Second, to those remaining: 'Wave your arm or move so we can find you' — those who wave or make purposeful movements are assessed second. Casualties who are still, or with obvious life threats such as massive bleeding, are assessed first. Sorting prioritizes individual assessment without touching anyone yet."},{"title":"Step 2/3 — Assess with Lifesaving Interventions","content":"Each casualty gets a rapid individual assessment combined with only those lifesaving interventions that take seconds: control massive hemorrhage (tourniquet or direct pressure), open the airway with positioning (for a child, consider giving two rescue breaths), chest decompression for tension pneumothorax (trained providers), and auto-injector antidotes (such as for nerve agents). These are done immediately, during triage, before assigning a category — and the triage officer then moves on rather than staying to treat."},{"title":"Assigning Categories: The Assessment Questions","content":"After lifesaving interventions, ask in sequence: Is the casualty breathing? If not (adult) — Dead. Does the casualty obey commands or make purposeful movements? Is there a peripheral pulse? Are they not in respiratory distress? Is major hemorrhage controlled? If ALL yes: the casualty is Minimal if the injuries are minor, otherwise Delayed. If ANY no: the casualty is Immediate — unless the injuries are so severe that survival is unlikely given the resources currently available, in which case Expectant."},{"title":"The Five SALT Categories","content":"Immediate (red): life-threatening injuries, likely to survive with prompt care — first priority for treatment and transport. Delayed (yellow): significant injuries, but care can wait without immediate threat to life. Minimal (green): walking wounded with minor injuries. Expectant (gray): alive, but survival unlikely with the resources currently available — receives comfort care and is re-triaged if resources improve. Dead (black): not breathing after airway opening. The expectant category exists precisely because resources are limited; it is a resource decision, not an abandonment."},{"title":"Triage Is Dynamic","content":"Triage decisions are made with incomplete information and changing resources, so they must be repeated: at the scene, at the treatment area, before transport, and on hospital arrival. A Delayed patient can deteriorate to Immediate; an Expectant patient can be upgraded when more resources arrive. Triage tags or visible markings communicate categories, and re-triage keeps them honest."}],"clinicalPearls":["SALT's global sort triages the crowd before you touch a single patient — voice commands do the first pass for you.","Lifesaving interventions during triage are limited to seconds-long actions: hemorrhage control, airway positioning (± 2 breaths for a child), chest decompression, auto-injector antidotes.","An apneic adult after airway opening is Dead in SALT; a child gets consideration of two rescue breaths first — consistent with the hypoxic nature of pediatric arrest.","Expectant is not Dead: comfort care always, and re-triage when resources improve."],"redFlags":["The triage officer stopping to provide prolonged care — triage halts and the scene backs up.","Ignoring the quiet, still casualties while treating the loudest ones.","Never re-triaging: categories assigned in the first 10 minutes silently become wrong."],"commonMistakes":["Treating walking wounded as 'fine' — they are assessed last, but they still get assessed.","Confusing Expectant (gray, alive) with Dead (black).","Spending minutes on CPR during mass-casualty triage — resource-intensive care for one apneic casualty costs many salvageable lives."],"memoryAids":["SALT: Sort, Assess, Lifesaving interventions, Treatment/transport.","Sort commands: 'Walk' → assess third; 'Wave' → assess second; Still/obvious threat → assess first.","Categories: Red now, Yellow later, Green walks, Gray waits with comfort, Black is gone."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"SALT Individual Assessment","content":"Casualty (after global sort)\n  → Lifesaving interventions as needed (seconds only):\n     bleeding control | airway positioning (child: consider 2 breaths) | chest decompression | auto-injector\n  → Breathing?\n     → No (adult): DEAD (black)\n     → No (child, after breaths): DEAD\n     → Yes:\n        → Obeys commands / purposeful movement?\n        → Peripheral pulse present?\n        → No respiratory distress?\n        → Major hemorrhage controlled?\n           → ALL yes + minor injuries only: MINIMAL (green)\n           → ALL yes + significant injuries: DELAYED (yellow)\n           → ANY no + likely to survive with current resources: IMMEDIATE (red)\n           → ANY no + survival unlikely with current resources: EXPECTANT (gray)\n  → Tag, move on, and RE-TRIAGE at every stage"}],"references":["NDLSF BDLS v4.0 — Mass-Casualty Triage and SALT","CDC-sponsored SALT Mass Casualty Triage consensus guideline"]},"c05":{"id":"c05","title":"Natural Disasters","shortTitle":"Natural Disasters","estimatedStudyTime":32,"difficulty":"Beginner","learningObjectives":["Describe the characteristic injury and illness patterns of major natural disaster types.","Explain why most flood and hurricane deaths are preventable drownings.","Recognize crush injury and crush syndrome after structural collapse.","Describe health effects of extreme heat and cold events.","Explain the public-health consequences that follow natural disasters.","Apply the DISASTER Paradigm to natural events."],"summary":[{"title":"Each Hazard Has a Signature","content":"Natural disasters produce predictable injury patterns — the 'signature' of the hazard. Knowing the signature lets responders anticipate casualties before assessment: drowning in floods, crush and dust injuries in earthquakes, penetrating debris trauma in tornadoes, and heat illness in heat waves. Anticipation drives the support requests and hospital warnings of the DISASTER Paradigm."},{"title":"Hurricanes and Floods","content":"Most hurricane and flood deaths are drownings, and many involve vehicles driven into floodwater — which is why 'turn around, don't drown' is a mitigation message. Other threats: blunt trauma from debris, electrocution from downed lines and generators, carbon monoxide poisoning from indoor generator use, wound infections from contaminated water, and the exacerbation of chronic disease when medications, dialysis, and oxygen supplies are lost. The health system impact often outlasts the storm by weeks."},{"title":"Earthquakes: Crush Injury and Crush Syndrome","content":"Earthquake casualties cluster around structural collapse: fractures, head injuries, and entrapment. Prolonged compression of muscle causes crush injury; when the compression is released, the systemic reperfusion of muscle breakdown products — potassium, myoglobin, acids — produces crush syndrome: hyperkalemia with dysrhythmias, myoglobinuric kidney injury, and shock. Aggressive fluid resuscitation ideally begins BEFORE extrication, and sudden death at release is a known hazard. Aftershocks endanger rescuers and demand continuous hazard reassessment."},{"title":"Tornadoes and Severe Wind","content":"Tornadoes hurl debris at ballistic speeds, producing penetrating trauma, complex contaminated wounds, fractures, and head injuries. Casualties are often concentrated along a narrow damage path, and wounds are heavily contaminated with soil and foreign material — tetanus prophylaxis and delayed closure considerations matter. Damaged infrastructure complicates access and transport."},{"title":"Extreme Heat and Cold","content":"Heat waves are among the deadliest natural hazards, killing through heat stroke — hyperthermia with altered mental status, a true emergency treated with rapid active cooling. The vulnerable die quietly at home: the elderly, the isolated, those without air conditioning, people on medications impairing thermoregulation. Cold events kill through hypothermia and carbon monoxide poisoning from improvised heating. Both extremes surge EDs with exacerbations of cardiac, respiratory, and renal disease."},{"title":"The Public-Health Tail","content":"After the acute phase, natural disasters leave a long public-health tail: displaced populations in shelters (with infectious disease, medication, and mental-health needs), damaged water and sanitation systems, vector increases, interrupted chronic care, and mold and remediation hazards. Disaster medicine includes anticipating and staffing this tail, not just the first 24 hours."}],"clinicalPearls":["Ask what the hazard's signature is and you will know your casualties before they arrive.","In crush entrapment, start aggressive IV fluids before releasing the compression — the release is the physiologic danger point.","After storms, think carbon monoxide: generators run indoors kill quietly, often whole families.","Heat stroke = hyperthermia + altered mental status: cool first, transport cooling."],"redFlags":["Rescuers entering unstable structures between aftershocks without engineering clearance.","A 'rescued' entrapped patient who deteriorates suddenly after release — reperfusion hyperkalemia.","Shelter populations with fever clusters — infectious outbreaks follow crowding."],"commonMistakes":["Treating floodwater as clean — wounds exposed to it are contaminated and infection-prone.","Releasing prolonged compression before fluid resuscitation and monitoring are ready.","Planning only for storm-day casualties and ignoring the weeks-long chronic-care surge."],"memoryAids":["Floods drown, quakes crush, tornadoes shred, heat cooks, cold + generators poison.","Crush syndrome: released muscle sends up the 3 M's — myoglobin, metabolic acid, and (hyper)kalemia (K⁺).","'Turn around, don't drown' — vehicles are where flood deaths happen."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Entrapped Casualty With Prolonged Compression","content":"Casualty entrapped with compressed limb/torso (>~1 hour)\n  → Scene/structural safety first (aftershocks, collapse)\n  → BEFORE release: IV access + aggressive isotonic fluids; cardiac monitoring if available\n  → Anticipate at release: hyperkalemia (dysrhythmia), hypotension, myoglobinuria\n  → Release → reassess immediately; treat dysrhythmias per protocol\n  → Rapid transport — flag as crush syndrome risk (renal protection, potassium management)"}],"references":["NDLSF BDLS v4.0 — Natural Disasters","NDLSF BDLS v4.0 — Public Health Consequences of Disasters"]},"c06":{"id":"c06","title":"Traumatic & Explosive Events","shortTitle":"Explosive Events","estimatedStudyTime":34,"difficulty":"Intermediate","learningObjectives":["Classify blast injuries into primary through quinary mechanisms.","Describe the organs most vulnerable to primary blast injury.","Recognize blast lung and its management cautions.","Describe scene priorities at an intentional explosive event, including secondary devices.","Explain the typical casualty distribution of bombings and its triage implications.","Apply hemorrhage-control priorities to blast and active-violence casualties."],"summary":[{"title":"The Five Blast Injury Mechanisms","content":"Blast injuries are classified by mechanism. Primary: the blast pressure wave itself, damaging air-filled organs. Secondary: fragments and debris propelled by the explosion — the most common cause of injury and death. Tertiary: the body being thrown against objects or the ground. Quaternary: everything else — burns, crush from collapse, smoke inhalation, exacerbated chronic illness. Quinary: injuries from additives to the device such as radiological material, chemicals, or biological contamination ('dirty' additives)."},{"title":"Primary Blast Injury: Air-Filled Organs","content":"The pressure wave injures where air meets tissue. Tympanic membrane rupture is the most common primary injury (though its absence does not exclude other blast injury). Blast lung — pulmonary contusion, hemorrhage, and alveolar rupture — is the most lethal, presenting with dyspnea, hypoxia, and hemoptysis, sometimes hours after exposure. The gastrointestinal tract can perforate or hemorrhage, especially in enclosed-space or underwater blasts. Air emboli from disrupted alveoli can cause stroke-like deficits or sudden death."},{"title":"Blast Lung Cautions","content":"Suspect blast lung in any survivor of a significant blast — especially enclosed-space — with respiratory symptoms. Give oxygen, but ventilate cautiously: positive pressure can worsen alveolar rupture and precipitate air embolism or pneumothorax, so use the lowest effective pressures and watch for tension physiology. Enclosed-space explosions multiply the pressure wave by reflection, raising the incidence and severity of primary injury."},{"title":"The Intentional Scene","content":"Bombings are crime scenes with responder-targeting risk. Priorities: stage until law enforcement addresses secondary devices, control the perimeter, preserve evidence where care allows, and coordinate with law enforcement under unified command. The DISASTER Paradigm's safety and hazard components dominate the first minutes. In active-violence events, casualty care follows the phased approach — threat suppression first, hemorrhage control in warm zones, full care in cold zones."},{"title":"Casualty Distribution and 'Upside-Down' Triage","content":"Bombings characteristically produce a wave of walking wounded who self-transport to the nearest hospital within minutes — arriving BEFORE the critical casualties, who need extrication and EMS transport. Hospitals must anticipate this 'upside-down' arrival order: the first patients through the door are usually the least injured, and the sickest arrive 30–60 minutes later, when the ED is already saturated. Reserving capacity for the delayed critical wave is a command decision."},{"title":"Hemorrhage Control Priorities","content":"Preventable death in blast and penetrating MCIs is dominated by extremity hemorrhage. Tourniquets applied early — including by bystanders, per Stop the Bleed principles — save lives, and they are one of SALT's triage-phase lifesaving interventions. Junctional wounds need packing and direct pressure. Whole-scene thinking applies: distribute casualties, re-triage relentlessly, and remember occult primary blast injury in anyone near the detonation."}],"clinicalPearls":["Secondary (fragment) injury — not the pressure wave — is the most common cause of bombing death and injury.","Enclosed-space blast = worse primary injury: reflected pressure waves multiply the dose.","Blast lung can declare itself hours later — observe significant exposures even if initially well.","Expect the walking wounded to reach the hospital before the critical patients; hold capacity for the second wave."],"redFlags":["Dyspnea, hypoxia, or hemoptysis after a blast — blast lung until proven otherwise.","Responders converging on the scene before secondary-device clearance.","Neurologic deficits or sudden collapse after a blast — consider arterial air embolism."],"commonMistakes":["Using an intact tympanic membrane to rule out primary blast injury — it cannot.","Ventilating blast lung with high pressures, precipitating pneumothorax or air embolism.","Filling every hospital bed with the first (walking) wave, leaving nothing for the delayed critical wave."],"memoryAids":["Blast 1-2-3-4-5: 1 pressure (air organs), 2 fragments, 3 thrown, 4 everything else, 5 dirty additives.","Primary blast targets the 3 airspaces: Ears, Lungs, Gut.","Bombing arrivals are upside-down: green wave first, red wave later."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Blast Casualty Assessment","content":"Blast survivor\n  → Scene: staged? secondary devices addressed? unified command with LE?\n  → Massive hemorrhage: tourniquet/packing FIRST (SALT lifesaving intervention)\n  → Airway/breathing: O2; suspect blast lung (dyspnea, hypoxia, hemoptysis)\n     → Ventilate gently if needed — low pressures; watch for pneumothorax\n  → Circulation: treat shock; consider GI blast injury in enclosed-space exposure\n  → Neuro deficit/sudden collapse: consider air embolism\n  → Ears ringing/TM rupture: marker of exposure, NOT a rule-out for other injury\n  → Enclosed-space or significant exposure: observe even if initially well"}],"references":["NDLSF BDLS v4.0 — Explosive and Traumatic Events","CDC — Blast Injury classification (as taught in BDLS v4.0)"]},"c07":{"id":"c07","title":"Chemical Events & Decontamination","shortTitle":"Chemical & Decon","estimatedStudyTime":36,"difficulty":"Intermediate","learningObjectives":["Recognize scene clues suggesting a chemical release.","Describe the major chemical agent classes and their toxidromes.","Recognize the cholinergic toxidrome of nerve agents and organophosphates.","Explain the principles and priority of decontamination.","Describe hot, warm, and cold zone organization and PPE concepts.","Explain antidote principles at the awareness level."],"summary":[{"title":"Detecting a Chemical Event","content":"Chemical releases announce themselves through pattern: multiple casualties collapsing in one area with similar sudden symptoms, dead animals or insects, unusual odors or visible clouds, and symptom onset tied to a location. The BDLS detection mindset — recognizing that a toxidrome cluster means a chemical scene, not a medical coincidence — protects responders from walking into the agent."},{"title":"Agent Classes and Toxidromes","content":"Nerve agents and organophosphate pesticides cause the cholinergic toxidrome. Vesicants (mustard, lewisite) blister skin, eyes, and airways — mustard's effects are typically delayed hours. Pulmonary/choking agents (chlorine, phosgene) injure the airways and cause pulmonary edema, phosgene often after a delay. Asphyxiants such as cyanide block cellular oxygen use, causing rapid collapse, seizures, and cardiac arrest despite normal-appearing oxygenation. Riot-control agents cause intense but usually self-limited eye, skin, and airway irritation."},{"title":"The Cholinergic Toxidrome","content":"Nerve agents inhibit acetylcholinesterase, flooding synapses with acetylcholine. The muscarinic signs are captured by SLUDGE (Salivation, Lacrimation, Urination, Defecation, GI distress, Emesis) or DUMBELS (Defecation, Urination, Miosis, Bronchorrhea/Bronchospasm, Emesis, Lacrimation, Salivation) — with the killer B's: bronchorrhea, bronchospasm, and bradycardia. Nicotinic effects add muscle twitching, weakness, and paralysis; central effects add seizures and apnea. Pinpoint pupils in a collapsing casualty cluster should scream nerve agent."},{"title":"Decontamination: The Core Intervention","content":"Decontamination protects the patient from continued absorption and protects responders and hospitals from secondary contamination. Removing clothing eliminates a large majority of contamination; the remainder is addressed with copious water (with gentle soap for oily agents), from head down, ideally within minutes. Gross decon before or during triage takes priority for symptomatic liquid exposures — an antidote given to a still-contaminated patient is a losing race. Dry powder agents are brushed off before water. Never delay life-saving decon to wait for a perfect setup."},{"title":"Zones and PPE","content":"Chemical scenes are organized into a hot zone (contamination present — entry only with appropriate protection), a warm zone (decontamination corridor), and a cold zone (clean support and treatment area). Casualties flow hot → warm (decon) → cold (treatment). PPE is selected for the hazard: the highest protection levels include self-contained breathing apparatus; most healthcare decon teams operate in lower levels with powered air-purifying respirators per facility protocol. Unprotected providers stay in the cold zone — a contaminated hospital is a closed hospital."},{"title":"Antidote Principles","content":"Awareness-level antidote knowledge: nerve agents — atropine (dries secretions, treats bradycardia; dosed to effect on secretions) plus pralidoxime (reactivates the enzyme), commonly packaged in auto-injectors that SALT triage permits during the lifesaving-interventions step, and benzodiazepines for seizures. Cyanide — hydroxocobalamin is the preferred antidote. Pulmonary agents and vesicants have no specific antidote: care is decon, oxygen, and supportive management. Antidote stockpiles (e.g., CHEMPACK-type caches) exist regionally; knowing they exist is a BDLS competency."}],"clinicalPearls":["Multiple casualties + one location + same sudden toxidrome = chemical scene; stage uphill, upwind, and upstream.","Clothing removal alone eliminates the large majority of contamination — it is the fastest, highest-yield decon step.","Pinpoint pupils, secretions everywhere, twitching: think nerve agent; atropine is dosed to dry secretions, not to a fixed number.","Cyanide collapse in an enclosed-space fire victim: consider hydroxocobalamin early."],"redFlags":["Responders or ED staff developing symptoms after touching an undeconned casualty — secondary contamination.","Sudden collapse of multiple workers in a confined space — asphyxiant until proven otherwise; do not enter unprotected.","Delayed dyspnea hours after a 'minor' chlorine or phosgene exposure — evolving pulmonary edema."],"commonMistakes":["Transporting contaminated patients directly to the ED, contaminating the facility.","Waiting for a formal decon corridor before removing clothing from a soaked, symptomatic patient.","Underdosing atropine in severe nerve-agent poisoning — titrate to drying of secretions.","Water-flushing a dry powder agent before brushing it off."],"memoryAids":["SLUDGE / DUMBELS for muscarinic signs; the killer B's — bronchorrhea, bronchospasm, bradycardia.","Decon order: clothes off (most of the job), then water head-to-toe.","Zones: Hot = agent, Warm = decon, Cold = care.","Stage uphill, upwind, upstream."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Suspected Chemical Release Response","content":"Cluster of collapsing casualties / unusual odor / dead animals\n  → STAGE uphill, upwind, upstream; do NOT enter unprotected\n  → Establish zones: hot / warm (decon) / cold\n  → Protected teams: extract casualties to decon corridor\n  → DECON: clothing off → copious water (brush dry powder first)\n  → SALT triage with lifesaving interventions incl. antidote auto-injectors\n  → Toxidrome-based care in cold zone:\n     Cholinergic → atropine (to secretions) + pralidoxime + benzos for seizures\n     Cyanide → hydroxocobalamin\n     Pulmonary agents/vesicants → oxygen + supportive; observe for delayed edema\n  → Notify hospitals: decon status of incoming patients"}],"references":["NDLSF BDLS v4.0 — Chemical Events","NDLSF BDLS v4.0 — Decontamination and Personal Protective Equipment"]},"c08":{"id":"c08","title":"Biological Events & Pandemics","shortTitle":"Biological Events","estimatedStudyTime":34,"difficulty":"Intermediate","learningObjectives":["Distinguish an overt from a covert biological event.","Explain the role of syndromic surveillance and epidemiologic clues in detection.","List the CDC bioterrorism agent categories and name key Category A agents.","Describe isolation precautions and personal protective equipment for biological threats.","Explain the public-health tools of a biological response (isolation, quarantine, prophylaxis).","Describe pandemic principles: surge, PPE conservation, and continuity."],"summary":[{"title":"Overt vs Covert Biological Events","content":"A biological event may be overt — an announced release or an obvious outbreak — or covert, revealing itself only days later as patients fall ill. Because most biological agents have an incubation period, the 'scene' of a covert event is not a place but a pattern in the population: the first responders are often clinicians and epidemiologists, not EMS at a cordon. This makes recognition the pivotal skill."},{"title":"Detection: Surveillance and Epidemiologic Clues","content":"Syndromic surveillance monitors patterns — ED visits, pharmacy sales, absenteeism — for signals of an emerging event. Epidemiologic clues that should raise suspicion of an intentional or unusual biological event include: a disease unusual for the area or season; an unusually severe or rapidly fatal illness; a point-source outbreak with many people ill at once; illness in an unexpected population; unusual routes of exposure; and simultaneous clusters in separate locations. Reporting suspicions to public health early is the health professional's key contribution."},{"title":"CDC Agent Categories","content":"The CDC classifies bioterrorism agents by risk. Category A — highest priority — are easily disseminated or transmitted, cause high mortality, and require special public-health preparedness: anthrax, botulism (botulinum toxin), plague, smallpox, tularemia, and viral hemorrhagic fevers (a useful mnemonic is 'A B PLoT' — Anthrax, Botulism, Plague, smallpox [variola], Tularemia, and viral hemorrhagic fevers). Category B agents are moderately easy to disseminate with lower mortality; Category C are emerging pathogens that could be engineered for mass spread."},{"title":"Isolation Precautions and PPE","content":"Protection matches the transmission route. Standard precautions always apply. Contact precautions (gown, gloves) address organisms spread by touch. Droplet precautions (surgical mask within close range) address agents like plague pneumonia. Airborne precautions (negative-pressure room and a fitted respirator such as an N95 or higher) address smallpox, tuberculosis, and measles. Some high-consequence pathogens (e.g., viral hemorrhagic fevers) require enhanced ensembles. Knowing which precaution a suspected agent demands — before the patient is in your face — is a core competency."},{"title":"Public-Health Response Tools","content":"Biological events are managed with public-health tools layered on clinical care: isolation (separating the ill), quarantine (restricting the exposed-but-well), post-exposure prophylaxis and vaccination (e.g., antibiotics for anthrax exposure, vaccination for smallpox), the Strategic National Stockpile for medications and supplies, and mass prophylaxis dispensing sites (points of dispensing, PODs). Contact tracing and clear risk communication limit spread and panic. These operate at the population level, coordinated by public-health authorities within the incident-management structure."},{"title":"Pandemic Principles","content":"A pandemic is a prolonged, widespread biological event that stresses the health system for months. Principles: protect the workforce (PPE, vaccination, and PPE conservation/extended use when supplies are constrained), expand surge capacity, maintain continuity of essential services, use crisis standards of care if demand overwhelms resources, and rely on non-pharmaceutical interventions (distancing, hygiene, masking, isolation) especially before specific vaccines or therapeutics exist. Responder mental health and sustainable staffing are strategic assets over a long event."}],"clinicalPearls":["In a covert biological event, the clinician IS the detector — an unusual case reported early can trigger the whole response.","Category A mnemonic: 'A B PLoT' — Anthrax, Botulism, Plague, smallpox, Tularemia, viral hemorrhagic fevers.","Match PPE to route: contact, droplet, or airborne — and default to higher protection when the agent is unknown.","Isolation is for the ill; quarantine is for the exposed-but-well — don't mix the terms."],"redFlags":["A disease appearing out of season, out of region, or in an unexpected population.","A point-source cluster: many previously well people acutely ill in the same short window.","Simultaneous outbreaks of the same illness in geographically separate places."],"commonMistakes":["Waiting for laboratory confirmation before notifying public health — early suspicion drives the response.","Applying the wrong precaution level (e.g., a surgical mask for an airborne agent like smallpox).","Confusing isolation with quarantine, or assuming quarantine applies to the sick."],"memoryAids":["Category A = 'A B PLoT': Anthrax, Botulism, Plague, smallpox, Tularemia, viral hemorrhagic fevers.","Epi clues: wrong disease, wrong place, wrong season, wrong population, too many at once, or in two places at once.","PPE by route: touch → contact; close-range spray → droplet; air → airborne (N95+ and negative pressure)."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Suspected Biological Event","content":"Unusual illness pattern observed\n  → Recognize epi clues (wrong disease/place/season/population; point source; multi-site)\n  → NOTIFY public health immediately — do not wait for confirmation\n  → Isolate the ill; apply route-appropriate PPE (default higher if unknown)\n     Touch → contact | Close droplets → droplet | Airborne (smallpox/TB) → airborne + N95/negative pressure\n  → Support public-health measures: quarantine of exposed, prophylaxis/vaccination, PODs, contact tracing\n  → For pandemics: protect and conserve the workforce, surge, continuity, crisis standards if overwhelmed"}],"references":["NDLSF BDLS v4.0 — Biological Events and Pandemics","CDC — Bioterrorism agent categories and isolation precautions (as taught in BDLS v4.0)"]},"c09":{"id":"c09","title":"Nuclear & Radiological Events","shortTitle":"Nuclear & Radiological","estimatedStudyTime":34,"difficulty":"Intermediate","learningObjectives":["Distinguish irradiation, external contamination, and internal contamination.","Apply the principles of time, distance, and shielding to responder protection.","Describe the types of radiological/nuclear events, including RDDs and improvised nuclear devices.","Recognize acute radiation syndrome and its dose-dependent course.","Explain that trauma care takes priority over decontamination in contaminated patients.","Describe radiological decontamination and the role of potassium iodide."],"summary":[{"title":"Three Distinct Concepts: Irradiation vs Contamination","content":"Radiation injury is confused when three ideas are blurred. Irradiation (exposure) is being in a radiation field — like an X-ray; once the person leaves the field, they are NOT radioactive and pose no risk to others. External contamination is radioactive material on the skin or clothing — it can be removed and can spread to responders. Internal contamination is radioactive material taken into the body by inhalation, ingestion, or wounds — it must be managed medically. Understanding which is present drives the entire response and calms unfounded fear of 'catching' radiation from an irradiated patient."},{"title":"Time, Distance, Shielding","content":"Responder protection rests on three levers. Time: minimize the duration of exposure. Distance: dose falls sharply with distance from the source (inverse-square relationship) — stepping back is powerful protection. Shielding: put mass (walls, vehicles, earth) between you and the source. These principles let responders work safely near radiological hazards. Standard PPE prevents contamination of skin and airway but does NOT stop penetrating gamma radiation — for that, distance and shielding matter most."},{"title":"Types of Radiological/Nuclear Events","content":"Events span a wide range. A radiological exposure device is a hidden source irradiating people without their knowledge. A radiological dispersal device (RDD, or 'dirty bomb') uses conventional explosives to scatter radioactive material — its immediate harm is the blast, with contamination as a secondary and psychological threat. Nuclear reactor or transport accidents release material over an area. An improvised nuclear device or nuclear detonation combines blast, thermal burns, and radiation on a catastrophic scale. Most realistic events are contamination and exposure problems layered on conventional trauma."},{"title":"Acute Radiation Syndrome (ARS)","content":"High whole-body doses cause acute radiation syndrome, which unfolds in stages: a prodrome (nausea, vomiting — the sooner and more severe the vomiting, the higher the dose), a latent period of apparent improvement, then manifest illness affecting the most radiosensitive systems. The hematopoietic system fails first (dropping blood counts, infection, bleeding), then at higher doses the gastrointestinal system (severe diarrhea, fluid loss), and at the highest doses the cardiovascular/central nervous system (rapidly fatal). Time-to-vomiting and lymphocyte-count trends help estimate dose and prognosis."},{"title":"Trauma First, Then Decontamination","content":"The cardinal rule: life-threatening injuries are treated before radiological decontamination. External contamination is rarely an immediate threat to the patient or, with standard precautions, to the provider — so airway, breathing, and hemorrhage control come first. Removing clothing eliminates most external contamination, and gentle washing handles the rest. Responders use standard precautions and radiation monitoring; wounds and body orifices are addressed to limit internal contamination. Stabilize the patient, then decontaminate."},{"title":"Radiological Decontamination and KI","content":"Decontamination mirrors chemical decon in principle: remove clothing (eliminating the majority of contamination), then wash gently with soap and water, working from wounds outward and avoiding abrasion that could drive material inward. Contaminated waste and clothing are contained. Potassium iodide (KI) is a specific, limited countermeasure: it saturates the thyroid to block uptake of radioactive iodine, protecting against thyroid cancer — it does NOT protect against other radionuclides or against external radiation, and it is most useful for exposures involving radioiodine (e.g., reactor releases). Psychological care and clear communication are major components, as radiation fear is powerful and often exceeds the physical risk."}],"clinicalPearls":["An irradiated (exposed) patient is not radioactive — like someone who had an X-ray, they cannot contaminate you.","Time, distance, shielding: doubling your distance cuts dose dramatically — step back before you do anything else.","Treat life threats before decontamination — trauma kills faster than external contamination.","Time-to-vomiting is a rapid dose estimator: earlier and more severe vomiting means a higher dose."],"redFlags":["Vomiting within minutes of a suspected high-dose exposure — a marker of severe ARS.","A rapidly falling lymphocyte count over the first day — poor prognostic sign in ARS.","Responders neglecting distance/shielding because they are wearing PPE — PPE does not stop gamma rays."],"commonMistakes":["Delaying resuscitation of a contaminated trauma patient to decontaminate first.","Believing an externally irradiated patient is dangerous to staff.","Giving potassium iodide as if it protected against all radiation (it only blocks thyroid radioiodine uptake)."],"memoryAids":["Three ideas: Irradiation (exposed, not radioactive), External contamination (on you), Internal contamination (in you).","Protect yourself with Time, Distance, Shielding.","Trauma before decon. Clothes off = most of the contamination gone.","KI protects one gland from one isotope — the thyroid from radioiodine."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Radiological/Nuclear Casualty Approach","content":"Suspected radiological event\n  → Protect responders: TIME, DISTANCE, SHIELDING; standard PPE; radiation monitoring\n  → Is the patient injured?\n     → Life-threatening injury: TREAT FIRST (airway, breathing, hemorrhage) — decon can wait\n     → Stable: proceed to decontamination\n  → Decontaminate: clothing off (most contamination) → gentle soap-and-water wash → contain waste\n  → Address internal contamination (wounds, orifices); consider KI ONLY for radioiodine exposure\n  → Estimate severity: time-to-vomiting, lymphocyte trend → ARS staging\n  → Reassure: irradiated (exposed) patients are not a hazard to others; manage radiation fear"}],"references":["NDLSF BDLS v4.0 — Nuclear and Radiological Events","NDLSF BDLS v4.0 — Radiation Protection and Acute Radiation Syndrome"]},"c10":{"id":"c10","title":"Surge Capacity, Psychosocial Care & Vulnerable Populations","shortTitle":"Surge, Psychosocial & CMIST","estimatedStudyTime":32,"difficulty":"Intermediate","learningObjectives":["Define surge capacity and the four S's (staff, stuff, space, systems).","Describe conventional, contingency, and crisis standards of care.","Recognize the psychological impact of disasters on survivors and responders.","Describe psychological first aid and responder resilience measures.","Explain the CMIST framework for at-risk and vulnerable populations.","Integrate these concepts into recovery and continuity planning."],"summary":[{"title":"Surge Capacity and the Four S's","content":"Surge capacity is a health system's ability to rapidly expand beyond normal services to meet a sudden increase in demand. It is built on four pillars — the four S's: Staff (clinical and support personnel, including callback and credentialed volunteers), Stuff (supplies, medications, equipment, PPE), Space (beds, alternate care sites, treatment areas), and Systems (command, communications, tracking, policies). A weakness in any one S caps the whole surge — plenty of beds are useless without staff to work them."},{"title":"Conventional, Contingency, Crisis Standards","content":"As demand rises, care moves along a continuum. Conventional care uses normal spaces, staff, and supplies. Contingency care uses adaptations that are functionally equivalent — repurposed spaces, substituted equipment, adjusted staffing ratios. Crisis standards of care are reached when demand overwhelms resources despite all adaptations, requiring a formally declared, ethically and legally framed shift to allocating scarce resources for population benefit. The goal throughout is to stay in conventional/contingency as long as possible and enter crisis standards deliberately, not by drift."},{"title":"The Psychological Toll","content":"Disasters injure minds as well as bodies. Survivors may experience acute stress reactions, grief, anxiety, depression, and later post-traumatic stress; the 'worried well' and psychological casualties can outnumber the physically injured, especially after radiological, chemical, or terrorist events. Pre-existing mental illness may decompensate when medications and routines are lost. Behavioral-health needs are part of the casualty count, not an afterthought."},{"title":"Psychological First Aid and Responder Resilience","content":"Psychological first aid (PFA) is the evidence-informed early response: ensure safety and basic needs, provide calm and comfort, connect people to loved ones and information, and link them to services — without forcing people to recount trauma. Responders themselves are at risk: cumulative stress, moral distress, and burnout degrade performance and health. Resilience measures include realistic training, work-rest cycles, buddy systems, leadership support, and post-event debriefing and follow-up. The recovery link of the disaster cycle includes caring for the caregivers."},{"title":"Vulnerable Populations and the CMIST Framework","content":"Disasters fall hardest on those least able to cope. The CMIST framework organizes access and functional needs across populations rather than by diagnosis: Communication (people with limited English, hearing, or vision needs), Maintaining health (those dependent on medications, oxygen, dialysis, or medical devices/power), Independence (people who rely on mobility aids, assistive devices, or personal-care attendants), Support/Safety/Self-determination (people needing supervision, including some with cognitive or psychiatric conditions, and children), and Transportation (those without independent means to evacuate). Planning to CMIST — not to labels — makes response equitable and effective."},{"title":"Tying It Together: Recovery and Continuity","content":"Surge, psychosocial care, and vulnerable-population planning all extend into the recovery phase. Continuity of operations keeps essential services running and restores the rest. Recovery addresses the long tail: rebuilding, chronic-care continuity, behavioral-health services for survivors and responders, and after-action review to feed lessons back into mitigation and preparedness. A response is not over when the last acute casualty is treated — it is over when the community and its responders have recovered."}],"clinicalPearls":["The four S's cap each other: staff, stuff, space, systems — the weakest S limits your surge.","Enter crisis standards of care deliberately and formally, never by accidental drift.","After many disasters the psychological casualties outnumber the physical ones — plan behavioral-health capacity.","Plan to CMIST functional needs, not to diagnostic labels — it captures who actually needs help and how."],"redFlags":["Surge plans that count beds (space) but ignore staff and systems.","Responders showing burnout, moral distress, or acute stress — performance and safety degrade.","Evacuation plans that strand people dependent on power, dialysis, mobility aids, or transportation."],"commonMistakes":["Treating behavioral-health needs as optional rather than as part of the casualty load.","Forcing survivors to recount their trauma in the name of 'debriefing' — not part of psychological first aid.","Planning for an 'average' patient and missing the access and functional needs of vulnerable groups."],"memoryAids":["Surge = four S's: Staff, Stuff, Space, Systems.","Standards continuum: Conventional → Contingency → Crisis.","CMIST: Communication, Maintaining health, Independence, Support/safety/self-determination, Transportation.","PFA: safety, calm, connectedness, self-efficacy, hope — comfort, don't interrogate."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Escalating Demand and Standards of Care","content":"Demand rising against capacity\n  → Maximize surge across the four S's: Staff, Stuff, Space, Systems\n  → Conventional care (normal resources) → if exceeded:\n  → Contingency care (functionally equivalent adaptations) → if exceeded:\n  → Crisis standards of care: FORMALLY declared; ethical/legal framework; allocate scarce resources for population benefit\n  → Throughout: address behavioral health (survivors + responders) and CMIST functional needs\n  → De-escalate back toward conventional as resources recover; after-action review"}],"references":["NDLSF BDLS v4.0 — Surge Capacity and Standards of Care","NDLSF BDLS v4.0 — Psychosocial Issues and At-Risk/Vulnerable Populations (CMIST)"]}},"flashcards":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","cards":[{"id":"c01_fc01","question":"What defines a disaster from the health-system perspective?","answer":"An event whose needs (casualties, hazards, infrastructure loss) exceed the resources immediately available to meet them — an imbalance, not a size threshold.","category":"Definitions"},{"id":"c01_fc02","question":"What is a mass-casualty incident (MCI)?","answer":"An event producing more patients than local resources can manage using routine procedures.","category":"Definitions"},{"id":"c01_fc03","question":"What is the all-hazards approach?","answer":"One common management framework that works across all disaster types (natural, explosive, chemical, biological, radiological), supplemented by hazard-specific annexes.","category":"Concepts"},{"id":"c01_fc04","question":"List the four phases of the disaster cycle.","answer":"Mitigation, Preparedness, Response, Recovery — a continuous cycle.","category":"Disaster Cycle"},{"id":"c01_fc05","question":"Give an example of mitigation.","answer":"Actions that reduce future impact: enforcing building codes, flood barriers, immunization programs.","category":"Disaster Cycle"},{"id":"c01_fc06","question":"What does the PRE-DISASTER Paradigm cover?","answer":"Pre-event readiness: Planning and practice, Resilience, and Education and training.","category":"PRE-DISASTER"},{"id":"c01_fc07","question":"What is the guiding ethical principle of disaster care?","answer":"The greatest good for the greatest number — allocating limited resources to benefit the most patients, unlike maximal individual care in daily practice.","category":"Concepts"},{"id":"c01_fc08","question":"Why does BDLS emphasize a common lexicon?","answer":"So physicians, nurses, EMS, and public-health workers from different agencies can integrate smoothly with shared vocabulary and expectations during a response.","category":"Concepts"},{"id":"c01_fc09","question":"Why is personal/family preparedness a system-level issue?","answer":"Staff with unprepared families may not report for duty; facility surge capacity depends on staff availability.","category":"Preparedness"},{"id":"c01_fc10","question":"What belongs in a responder's personal preparedness?","answer":"Family communication plan, go-kit with supplies and medications, arrangements for dependents and pets, and knowledge of workplace disaster roles.","category":"Preparedness"},{"id":"c01_fc11","question":"In which disaster phase does the DISASTER Paradigm operate?","answer":"The response phase — during and immediately after the event.","category":"Disaster Cycle"},{"id":"c01_fc12","question":"What is resilience in the PRE-DISASTER context?","answer":"The capacity of individuals, infrastructure, and communities to absorb a shock and recover from it.","category":"PRE-DISASTER"},{"id":"c01_fc13","question":"Why can the same event be a disaster in one place and not another?","answer":"Because the definition depends on local resources: a rural hospital may be overwhelmed by casualties a large trauma system absorbs routinely.","category":"Definitions"},{"id":"c01_fc14","question":"How does documentation change in disaster care?","answer":"It is abbreviated (e.g., triage tags) so that scarce provider time goes to patient care.","category":"Concepts"},{"id":"c01_fc15","question":"What is the danger of an unexercised disaster plan?","answer":"Plans that were never practiced fail under stress — exercising reveals gaps and builds the muscle memory the response phase requires.","category":"Preparedness"}]},"c02":{"chapter":"c02","cards":[{"id":"c02_fc01","question":"What does the DISASTER mnemonic stand for?","answer":"Detection, Incident command, Safety and security, Assess hazards, Support, Triage and treatment, Evacuation, Recovery.","category":"Framework"},{"id":"c02_fc02","question":"What question does the Detection step answer?","answer":"Do the needs of this event exceed the available resources — is this a disaster/MCI?","category":"Detection"},{"id":"c02_fc03","question":"Give an example of insidious (non-obvious) detection.","answer":"A covert biological event detected only as clusters of unusual symptoms across multiple emergency departments.","category":"Detection"},{"id":"c02_fc04","question":"Who establishes incident command initially?","answer":"The first trained responder on scene — command is announced and later transferred as more senior officers arrive.","category":"Incident Command"},{"id":"c02_fc05","question":"What is the safety priority order at a disaster scene?","answer":"Yourself first, then your team, then the public/bystanders, then the patients.","category":"Safety"},{"id":"c02_fc06","question":"Why does responder safety come before patient care?","answer":"An injured responder stops adding resources and starts consuming them, worsening the needs-resources gap.","category":"Safety"},{"id":"c02_fc07","question":"What are secondary devices?","answer":"Explosives or hazards deliberately timed/placed to injure responders after the initial event — a key reason hazard assessment is continuous.","category":"Hazards"},{"id":"c02_fc08","question":"Why must support be requested early?","answer":"Every resource arrives with a delay, so requests should anticipate the incident's needs an hour ahead, not its needs right now.","category":"Support"},{"id":"c02_fc09","question":"What triage method does BDLS teach for the Triage & treatment step?","answer":"SALT — Sort, Assess, Lifesaving interventions, Treatment and/or transport.","category":"Triage"},{"id":"c02_fc10","question":"What is the key principle of disaster evacuation/transport?","answer":"Distribute casualties across appropriate receiving facilities — sending everyone to the nearest hospital just relocates the disaster.","category":"Evacuation"},{"id":"c02_fc11","question":"When does recovery begin?","answer":"During the response — restoring systems, supporting responders and survivors, and capturing lessons learned start before the scene is closed.","category":"Recovery"},{"id":"c02_fc12","question":"What should the first radio report from a scene include?","answer":"The detection picture: estimated casualties, hazards present, resources needed, and that command is established.","category":"Detection"},{"id":"c02_fc13","question":"Why is 'freelancing' dangerous at a disaster scene?","answer":"Responders acting outside incident command break accountability, duplicate work, and endanger themselves and the operation.","category":"Incident Command"},{"id":"c02_fc14","question":"Name hazards to actively reassess during a response.","answer":"Fire, structural collapse, downed lines, hazmat, rising water, aftershocks, violence, and secondary devices.","category":"Hazards"},{"id":"c02_fc15","question":"Why is the DISASTER Paradigm called 'all-hazards'?","answer":"The same ordered checklist applies to any event type — flood, bombing, epidemic — giving all responders shared priorities.","category":"Framework"}]},"c03":{"chapter":"c03","cards":[{"id":"c03_fc01","question":"What is the Incident Command System (ICS)?","answer":"A standardized, scalable management structure providing common terminology, clear chain of command, defined roles, and integrated communications for any incident.","category":"ICS Basics"},{"id":"c03_fc02","question":"Name the five ICS functional sections.","answer":"Command, Operations, Planning, Logistics, and Finance/Administration.","category":"ICS Structure"},{"id":"c03_fc03","question":"What does the Operations section do?","answer":"The tactical work of the response: rescue, triage, treatment, and transport.","category":"ICS Structure"},{"id":"c03_fc04","question":"What does the Planning section do?","answer":"Collects and evaluates information, tracks resources, and prepares the incident action plan.","category":"ICS Structure"},{"id":"c03_fc05","question":"What does the Logistics section do?","answer":"Obtains everything the response needs — supplies, facilities, communications, food, and medical support for responders.","category":"ICS Structure"},{"id":"c03_fc06","question":"What does Finance/Administration handle?","answer":"Cost tracking, contracts and procurement, compensation/claims, and time records.","category":"ICS Structure"},{"id":"c03_fc07","question":"Who makes up the command staff?","answer":"The safety officer, public information officer, and liaison officer, working directly for the incident commander.","category":"ICS Structure"},{"id":"c03_fc08","question":"What unique authority does the safety officer hold?","answer":"The authority to immediately stop any operation that poses imminent danger.","category":"Safety"},{"id":"c03_fc09","question":"What is span of control in ICS?","answer":"One supervisor should directly manage about 3–7 people (classically 5); beyond that, the structure subdivides.","category":"ICS Principles"},{"id":"c03_fc10","question":"What is unified command?","answer":"A shared command arrangement in which key agencies/jurisdictions jointly set objectives under one coordinated plan with a single Operations section.","category":"ICS Principles"},{"id":"c03_fc11","question":"What is NIMS?","answer":"The National Incident Management System — the U.S. doctrine standardizing incident management (ICS, resource typing, credentialing, mutual aid, EOCs) across agencies and levels of government.","category":"NIMS"},{"id":"c03_fc12","question":"How does a hospital use incident command?","answer":"Through an ICS adaptation (e.g., HICS) applying the same five functions to facility problems — surge, staffing, supplies, evacuation — with roles defined by job action sheets.","category":"Hospital ICS"},{"id":"c03_fc13","question":"In ICS, who do you take direction from?","answer":"Your single assigned incident supervisor — not your everyday manager (unity of command).","category":"ICS Principles"},{"id":"c03_fc14","question":"How is command transferred?","answer":"Formally, with a briefing of the incoming commander, and an announcement so everyone knows who now commands.","category":"ICS Principles"},{"id":"c03_fc15","question":"What is the role of an Emergency Operations Center (EOC)?","answer":"Off-scene coordination and support — resources, information, policy — supporting (not replacing) on-scene incident command.","category":"NIMS"}]},"c04":{"chapter":"c04","cards":[{"id":"c04_fc01","question":"What does SALT stand for?","answer":"Sort, Assess, Lifesaving interventions, Treatment and/or transport — the CDC-sponsored national mass-casualty triage standard.","category":"Framework"},{"id":"c04_fc02","question":"What are the two global sorting commands?","answer":"1) 'If you can hear me and need help, walk to this area' (walkers assessed last). 2) 'Wave your arm or move' (wavers assessed second). Still casualties or obvious life threats are assessed first.","category":"Sort"},{"id":"c04_fc03","question":"List the rapid lifesaving interventions permitted during SALT triage.","answer":"Control massive hemorrhage, open the airway by positioning (child: consider 2 rescue breaths), chest decompression for tension pneumothorax (trained providers), and auto-injector antidotes.","category":"Lifesaving Interventions"},{"id":"c04_fc04","question":"Name the five SALT triage categories with colors.","answer":"Immediate (red), Delayed (yellow), Minimal (green), Expectant (gray), Dead (black).","category":"Categories"},{"id":"c04_fc05","question":"What are the SALT assessment questions after lifesaving interventions?","answer":"Breathing? Obeys commands/purposeful movement? Peripheral pulse? No respiratory distress? Major hemorrhage controlled?","category":"Assess"},{"id":"c04_fc06","question":"An adult remains apneic after airway opening during SALT. Category?","answer":"Dead (black). CPR is not performed during mass-casualty triage of an apneic adult.","category":"Categories"},{"id":"c04_fc07","question":"How does SALT treat an apneic child differently from an adult?","answer":"For a child, consider giving two rescue breaths after opening the airway; if breathing does not resume, the child is Dead. This reflects the hypoxic nature of pediatric arrest.","category":"Pediatric"},{"id":"c04_fc08","question":"What does the Expectant (gray) category mean?","answer":"Alive, but survival is unlikely with the resources CURRENTLY available. Comfort care is provided, and the patient is re-triaged if resources improve — it is not the same as Dead.","category":"Categories"},{"id":"c04_fc09","question":"A casualty answers all assessment questions 'yes' and has only minor injuries. Category?","answer":"Minimal (green).","category":"Categories"},{"id":"c04_fc10","question":"A casualty answers all questions 'yes' but has significant injuries. Category?","answer":"Delayed (yellow) — significant care needed, but it can wait.","category":"Categories"},{"id":"c04_fc11","question":"A casualty fails one assessment question but is salvageable with current resources. Category?","answer":"Immediate (red) — first priority for treatment and transport.","category":"Categories"},{"id":"c04_fc12","question":"Why must triage be repeated (re-triage)?","answer":"Patients deteriorate or improve and resources change; categories are reassessed at the scene, treatment area, transport, and hospital arrival.","category":"Dynamics"},{"id":"c04_fc13","question":"How is everyday triage different from mass-casualty triage?","answer":"Everyday triage finds the sickest patient for maximal individual care; mass-casualty triage rations limited resources to produce the most survivors overall.","category":"Concepts"},{"id":"c04_fc14","question":"Why doesn't the triage officer stop to treat patients?","answer":"Beyond seconds-long lifesaving interventions, stopping halts triage for everyone still unsorted — the officer tags and moves on.","category":"Concepts"},{"id":"c04_fc15","question":"Are the walking wounded 'cleared' by walking?","answer":"No — walking assigns them the last assessment priority, but every casualty still receives individual assessment; injuries hide in the green group.","category":"Sort"},{"id":"c04_fc16","question":"What tools communicate triage categories on scene?","answer":"Triage tags, colored tape/tarps, or other visible markings, updated at each re-triage.","category":"Dynamics"}]},"c05":{"chapter":"c05","cards":[{"id":"c05_fc01","question":"What is a disaster 'signature'?","answer":"The predictable injury/illness pattern of a hazard type — e.g., drowning in floods, crush in earthquakes — which lets responders anticipate casualties.","category":"Concepts"},{"id":"c05_fc02","question":"What is the leading cause of death in hurricanes and floods?","answer":"Drowning — frequently involving vehicles driven into floodwater.","category":"Floods"},{"id":"c05_fc03","question":"Why does carbon monoxide poisoning spike after storms?","answer":"Power outages lead people to run generators or charcoal indoors; CO is odorless and can poison whole families.","category":"Floods"},{"id":"c05_fc04","question":"What is crush injury?","answer":"Direct muscle and tissue damage from prolonged compression, typically in structural collapse entrapment.","category":"Earthquakes"},{"id":"c05_fc05","question":"What is crush syndrome?","answer":"The systemic reperfusion effects after compression release: hyperkalemia (dysrhythmias), myoglobinuria (kidney injury), acidosis, and shock.","category":"Earthquakes"},{"id":"c05_fc06","question":"When should fluid resuscitation begin for an entrapped crush patient?","answer":"Before extrication/release of the compression whenever possible — release is the physiologic danger point.","category":"Earthquakes"},{"id":"c05_fc07","question":"What electrolyte emergency kills crush patients at release?","answer":"Hyperkalemia — potassium from damaged muscle floods the circulation and can cause fatal dysrhythmias.","category":"Earthquakes"},{"id":"c05_fc08","question":"What is the tornado injury signature?","answer":"Ballistic debris: penetrating trauma, complex heavily contaminated wounds, fractures, and head injuries along a narrow damage path.","category":"Tornadoes"},{"id":"c05_fc09","question":"Why do tornado wounds need special attention?","answer":"They are contaminated with soil and foreign material — tetanus prophylaxis and consideration of delayed closure are important.","category":"Tornadoes"},{"id":"c05_fc10","question":"Define heat stroke.","answer":"Life-threatening hyperthermia with altered mental status — treated with immediate rapid active cooling, then transport (cool first).","category":"Heat & Cold"},{"id":"c05_fc11","question":"Who dies in heat waves?","answer":"The elderly, isolated people without cooling, and those on medications impairing thermoregulation — often quietly at home.","category":"Heat & Cold"},{"id":"c05_fc12","question":"What kills in cold events besides hypothermia?","answer":"Carbon monoxide poisoning from improvised indoor heating and house fires.","category":"Heat & Cold"},{"id":"c05_fc13","question":"What ongoing hazard endangers earthquake rescuers?","answer":"Aftershocks and progressive structural collapse — hazard assessment must be continuous.","category":"Earthquakes"},{"id":"c05_fc14","question":"What is the 'public-health tail' of a natural disaster?","answer":"Weeks of shelter health needs, water/sanitation failures, interrupted chronic care (dialysis, oxygen, medications), vectors, mold, and mental-health impacts.","category":"Public Health"},{"id":"c05_fc15","question":"Why do EDs surge for weeks after a hurricane?","answer":"Chronic disease decompensates when medications, dialysis, oxygen, and power-dependent devices are lost — the medical surge outlasts the trauma surge.","category":"Public Health"}]},"c06":{"chapter":"c06","cards":[{"id":"c06_fc01","question":"Name the five blast injury mechanisms.","answer":"Primary (pressure wave), Secondary (fragments/debris), Tertiary (body thrown), Quaternary (burns, crush, inhalation, everything else), Quinary (device additives — radiological/chemical/biological).","category":"Classification"},{"id":"c06_fc02","question":"Which blast mechanism causes the most injuries and deaths?","answer":"Secondary — fragments and debris propelled by the explosion.","category":"Classification"},{"id":"c06_fc03","question":"Which organs does primary blast injury target?","answer":"Air-filled organs: ears (tympanic membrane), lungs (blast lung), and gastrointestinal tract.","category":"Primary Blast"},{"id":"c06_fc04","question":"What is the most common primary blast injury?","answer":"Tympanic membrane rupture — though its absence does NOT rule out other primary blast injury.","category":"Primary Blast"},{"id":"c06_fc05","question":"What is blast lung and how does it present?","answer":"Pulmonary contusion/hemorrhage with alveolar rupture from the pressure wave: dyspnea, hypoxia, hemoptysis — sometimes delayed by hours.","category":"Primary Blast"},{"id":"c06_fc06","question":"Why must blast lung be ventilated cautiously?","answer":"Positive pressure can extend alveolar rupture, causing pneumothorax or arterial air embolism — use the lowest effective pressures.","category":"Primary Blast"},{"id":"c06_fc07","question":"Why are enclosed-space explosions worse?","answer":"Reflected pressure waves multiply the blast dose, increasing the incidence and severity of primary blast injury.","category":"Primary Blast"},{"id":"c06_fc08","question":"What can cause stroke-like deficits or sudden death after a blast?","answer":"Arterial air embolism from disrupted alveoli entering the circulation.","category":"Primary Blast"},{"id":"c06_fc09","question":"What scene hazard is unique to intentional bombings?","answer":"Secondary devices deliberately placed to injure responders — stage until law enforcement clears the scene.","category":"Scene"},{"id":"c06_fc10","question":"What is 'upside-down triage' at hospitals after a bombing?","answer":"Walking wounded self-transport and arrive first; the critical casualties arrive 30–60 minutes later — hospitals must reserve capacity for the second wave.","category":"Casualty Flow"},{"id":"c06_fc11","question":"What is the leading cause of preventable death in blast/penetrating MCIs?","answer":"Extremity hemorrhage — controlled by early tourniquets (a SALT lifesaving intervention and Stop the Bleed skill).","category":"Hemorrhage"},{"id":"c06_fc12","question":"What are quinary blast injuries?","answer":"Injuries from device additives — radiological ('dirty bomb'), chemical, or biological contamination added to the explosive.","category":"Classification"},{"id":"c06_fc13","question":"Being thrown against a wall by a blast is which mechanism?","answer":"Tertiary blast injury.","category":"Classification"},{"id":"c06_fc14","question":"Burns and smoke inhalation at a bombing are which mechanism?","answer":"Quaternary — the 'everything else' category including burns, crush from collapse, and inhalation.","category":"Classification"},{"id":"c06_fc15","question":"Why observe initially-well survivors of significant blasts?","answer":"Primary blast injuries — especially blast lung and GI injury — can present hours after exposure.","category":"Primary Blast"},{"id":"c06_fc16","question":"How does care proceed in active-violence events?","answer":"Phased: threat suppression first, hemorrhage control in warm zones, full care in cold zones — coordinated with law enforcement.","category":"Scene"}]},"c07":{"chapter":"c07","cards":[{"id":"c07_fc01","question":"What scene clues suggest a chemical release?","answer":"Multiple casualties collapsing in one area with similar sudden symptoms, dead animals/insects, unusual odors or clouds, and location-linked onset.","category":"Detection"},{"id":"c07_fc02","question":"Where should responders stage at a chemical scene?","answer":"Uphill, upwind, and upstream of the release — never entering unprotected.","category":"Scene"},{"id":"c07_fc03","question":"Name the major chemical agent classes.","answer":"Nerve agents/organophosphates, vesicants (blister agents), pulmonary/choking agents, asphyxiants (e.g., cyanide), and riot-control agents.","category":"Agents"},{"id":"c07_fc04","question":"What toxidrome do nerve agents cause?","answer":"Cholinergic: SLUDGE/DUMBELS muscarinic signs, nicotinic twitching/weakness, plus seizures and apnea — with miosis (pinpoint pupils).","category":"Nerve Agents"},{"id":"c07_fc05","question":"What are the 'killer B's' of nerve agent poisoning?","answer":"Bronchorrhea, bronchospasm, and bradycardia — the respiratory drowning and circulatory failure that kill.","category":"Nerve Agents"},{"id":"c07_fc06","question":"What are the nerve-agent antidotes?","answer":"Atropine (titrated until secretions dry) plus pralidoxime (2-PAM), often in auto-injectors; benzodiazepines for seizures.","category":"Antidotes"},{"id":"c07_fc07","question":"How is atropine dosed in nerve-agent poisoning?","answer":"Titrated to effect — repeated until bronchial secretions dry and ventilation is possible, not to a fixed maximum.","category":"Antidotes"},{"id":"c07_fc08","question":"What single decon step removes most contamination?","answer":"Removing the clothing — it eliminates a large majority of the contamination in seconds.","category":"Decon"},{"id":"c07_fc09","question":"What is the decon sequence for a dry powder agent?","answer":"Brush off the powder FIRST, then flush with copious water — some dry agents react with water.","category":"Decon"},{"id":"c07_fc10","question":"Define the hot, warm, and cold zones.","answer":"Hot: contamination present (protected entry only). Warm: the decontamination corridor. Cold: clean area for treatment and support. Casualties flow hot → warm → cold.","category":"Zones"},{"id":"c07_fc11","question":"What is secondary contamination?","answer":"Transfer of agent from a contaminated casualty to responders, equipment, or facilities — the reason undeconned patients must not enter the ED.","category":"Decon"},{"id":"c07_fc12","question":"How do vesicants like mustard present?","answer":"Blistering of skin, eyes, and airways — with mustard the effects are typically DELAYED several hours after exposure.","category":"Agents"},{"id":"c07_fc13","question":"How do pulmonary agents like chlorine and phosgene injure?","answer":"Airway irritation and pulmonary edema; phosgene classically causes delayed pulmonary edema hours after exposure.","category":"Agents"},{"id":"c07_fc14","question":"How does cyanide kill, and what is the preferred antidote?","answer":"It blocks cellular oxygen utilization causing rapid collapse, seizures, and arrest; hydroxocobalamin is the preferred antidote.","category":"Antidotes"},{"id":"c07_fc15","question":"When may antidote auto-injectors be given during triage?","answer":"During SALT's lifesaving-interventions step — a seconds-long intervention for casualties with the nerve-agent toxidrome.","category":"Triage"},{"id":"c07_fc16","question":"Why must gross decon precede ED entry?","answer":"A contaminated hospital becomes part of the incident: staff are poisoned, the facility may close, and regional capacity collapses.","category":"Decon"}]},"c08":{"chapter":"c08","cards":[{"id":"c08_fc01","question":"What is the difference between an overt and a covert biological event?","answer":"Overt: an announced release or obvious outbreak. Covert: revealed only later as people fall ill after the incubation period — detected as a population pattern, not a scene.","category":"Detection"},{"id":"c08_fc02","question":"Who are often the 'first responders' to a covert biological event?","answer":"Clinicians and epidemiologists who recognize an unusual illness pattern — not EMS at a cordon.","category":"Detection"},{"id":"c08_fc03","question":"What is syndromic surveillance?","answer":"Monitoring patterns (ED visits, pharmacy sales, absenteeism) for early signals of an emerging biological event before diagnoses are confirmed.","category":"Detection"},{"id":"c08_fc04","question":"Name epidemiologic clues to an intentional/unusual biological event.","answer":"Disease unusual for the area/season, unusually severe or rapidly fatal illness, point-source cluster, unexpected population, unusual exposure route, and simultaneous outbreaks in separate places.","category":"Detection"},{"id":"c08_fc05","question":"What are the Category A bioterrorism agents?","answer":"Anthrax, Botulism (botulinum toxin), Plague, Smallpox (variola), Tularemia, and Viral hemorrhagic fevers — 'A B PLoT'.","category":"Agents"},{"id":"c08_fc06","question":"What makes an agent Category A?","answer":"Easily disseminated or transmitted person-to-person, high mortality, potential for public panic, and need for special public-health preparedness.","category":"Agents"},{"id":"c08_fc07","question":"What PPE addresses an airborne agent like smallpox?","answer":"Airborne precautions: a fitted respirator (N95 or higher) and a negative-pressure room.","category":"PPE"},{"id":"c08_fc08","question":"What PPE addresses a droplet-spread agent like pneumonic plague?","answer":"Droplet precautions: a surgical mask within close range, plus standard precautions.","category":"PPE"},{"id":"c08_fc09","question":"What is the difference between isolation and quarantine?","answer":"Isolation separates people who are ill; quarantine restricts people who were exposed but are not yet ill.","category":"Public Health"},{"id":"c08_fc10","question":"What is post-exposure prophylaxis in a biological event?","answer":"Preventive treatment (e.g., antibiotics after anthrax exposure, vaccination for smallpox) given to exposed people to prevent disease.","category":"Public Health"},{"id":"c08_fc11","question":"What is the Strategic National Stockpile?","answer":"A national cache of medications, vaccines, and supplies deployable to supplement local resources during a large public-health emergency.","category":"Public Health"},{"id":"c08_fc12","question":"What is a POD (point of dispensing)?","answer":"A mass site for rapidly dispensing prophylactic medications or vaccines to a large exposed population.","category":"Public Health"},{"id":"c08_fc13","question":"What should a clinician do when a biological event is suspected?","answer":"Notify public health immediately — do not wait for laboratory confirmation — while isolating the ill and using route-appropriate PPE.","category":"Detection"},{"id":"c08_fc14","question":"What are non-pharmaceutical interventions (NPIs) in a pandemic?","answer":"Distancing, hygiene, masking, and isolation/quarantine — especially important before specific vaccines or therapeutics exist.","category":"Pandemic"},{"id":"c08_fc15","question":"Why is workforce protection central to pandemic response?","answer":"A long event depends on sustaining staff; PPE, vaccination, PPE conservation/extended use, and mental-health support keep the workforce functional.","category":"Pandemic"},{"id":"c08_fc16","question":"What are crisis standards of care?","answer":"A formally declared shift in care standards when demand overwhelms resources, allocating scarce resources for population benefit under legal/ethical frameworks.","category":"Pandemic"}]},"c09":{"chapter":"c09","cards":[{"id":"c09_fc01","question":"What is irradiation (radiation exposure)?","answer":"Being in a radiation field, like an X-ray. Once out of the field the person is NOT radioactive and poses no risk to others.","category":"Concepts"},{"id":"c09_fc02","question":"What is external contamination?","answer":"Radioactive material on the skin or clothing — it can be removed and can spread to responders and surfaces.","category":"Concepts"},{"id":"c09_fc03","question":"What is internal contamination?","answer":"Radioactive material taken into the body by inhalation, ingestion, or through wounds — managed medically.","category":"Concepts"},{"id":"c09_fc04","question":"What are the three principles of responder radiation protection?","answer":"Time (minimize exposure duration), Distance (dose falls sharply with distance), and Shielding (put mass between you and the source).","category":"Protection"},{"id":"c09_fc05","question":"Does standard PPE stop penetrating gamma radiation?","answer":"No — PPE prevents skin/airway contamination but does not stop gamma rays; distance and shielding are what reduce penetrating dose.","category":"Protection"},{"id":"c09_fc06","question":"What is a radiological dispersal device (RDD)?","answer":"A 'dirty bomb' — conventional explosives scattering radioactive material; the immediate harm is the blast, with contamination as a secondary and psychological threat.","category":"Event Types"},{"id":"c09_fc07","question":"What is the cardinal rule for a contaminated trauma patient?","answer":"Treat life-threatening injuries FIRST; radiological decontamination comes after stabilization.","category":"Care Priorities"},{"id":"c09_fc08","question":"What are the stages of acute radiation syndrome?","answer":"Prodrome (nausea/vomiting), latent period, and manifest illness — hematopoietic, then GI, then cardiovascular/CNS with increasing dose.","category":"ARS"},{"id":"c09_fc09","question":"What does time-to-vomiting indicate in ARS?","answer":"Dose severity — the sooner and more severe the vomiting, the higher the radiation dose and the worse the prognosis.","category":"ARS"},{"id":"c09_fc10","question":"Which body system fails first in ARS?","answer":"The hematopoietic system — falling blood counts leading to infection and bleeding.","category":"ARS"},{"id":"c09_fc11","question":"Is an externally irradiated (exposed) patient dangerous to staff?","answer":"No — like a patient who had an X-ray, they are not radioactive and cannot contaminate others.","category":"Concepts"},{"id":"c09_fc12","question":"What single step removes most external radiological contamination?","answer":"Removing the clothing.","category":"Decon"},{"id":"c09_fc13","question":"What does potassium iodide (KI) protect against?","answer":"It blocks the thyroid's uptake of RADIOACTIVE IODINE only — it does not protect against other radionuclides or external radiation.","category":"Countermeasures"},{"id":"c09_fc14","question":"How should you wash radiological contamination?","answer":"Gently with soap and water, working from wounds outward, avoiding abrasion that could drive material inward.","category":"Decon"},{"id":"c09_fc15","question":"Why is psychological care emphasized in radiological events?","answer":"Radiation fear is powerful and often exceeds the actual physical risk, driving worried-well surges and panic; clear communication is essential.","category":"Psychosocial"},{"id":"c09_fc16","question":"How does distance reduce radiation dose?","answer":"Dose falls with the inverse square of distance — moving farther from the source cuts exposure dramatically.","category":"Protection"}]},"c10":{"chapter":"c10","cards":[{"id":"c10_fc01","question":"What is surge capacity?","answer":"A health system's ability to rapidly expand beyond normal services to meet a sudden increase in demand.","category":"Surge"},{"id":"c10_fc02","question":"What are the four S's of surge capacity?","answer":"Staff, Stuff (supplies/equipment), Space, and Systems (command, communications, tracking, policies).","category":"Surge"},{"id":"c10_fc03","question":"Why is the 'weakest S' concept important?","answer":"A shortfall in any one S caps the entire surge — e.g., extra beds are useless without staff to work them.","category":"Surge"},{"id":"c10_fc04","question":"Define conventional, contingency, and crisis standards of care.","answer":"Conventional: normal resources. Contingency: functionally equivalent adaptations. Crisis: formally declared allocation of scarce resources when demand overwhelms all adaptations.","category":"Standards of Care"},{"id":"c10_fc05","question":"How should a system enter crisis standards of care?","answer":"Deliberately and formally, under an ethical/legal framework — never by accidental drift.","category":"Standards of Care"},{"id":"c10_fc06","question":"Why can psychological casualties outnumber physical ones?","answer":"Fear, acute stress, and the 'worried well' — especially after terrorist, chemical, or radiological events — generate large behavioral-health demand.","category":"Psychosocial"},{"id":"c10_fc07","question":"What is psychological first aid (PFA)?","answer":"An early, evidence-informed response: ensure safety and basic needs, provide calm and comfort, connect people to loved ones and information, and link to services — without forcing trauma recounting.","category":"Psychosocial"},{"id":"c10_fc08","question":"What are the core aims of PFA?","answer":"Promote safety, calm, connectedness, self-efficacy, and hope.","category":"Psychosocial"},{"id":"c10_fc09","question":"What threatens responders psychologically?","answer":"Cumulative stress, moral distress, and burnout, which degrade performance, health, and safety.","category":"Responder Care"},{"id":"c10_fc10","question":"Name responder resilience measures.","answer":"Realistic training, work-rest cycles, buddy systems, leadership support, and post-event debriefing and follow-up.","category":"Responder Care"},{"id":"c10_fc11","question":"What does the CMIST framework organize?","answer":"The access and functional needs of at-risk/vulnerable populations by function rather than by diagnosis.","category":"CMIST"},{"id":"c10_fc12","question":"What does CMIST stand for?","answer":"Communication, Maintaining health, Independence, Support/Safety/Self-determination, and Transportation.","category":"CMIST"},{"id":"c10_fc13","question":"Give an example of the 'Maintaining health' CMIST need.","answer":"People dependent on medications, oxygen, dialysis, or power-dependent medical devices who decompensate when infrastructure fails.","category":"CMIST"},{"id":"c10_fc14","question":"Why plan to functional needs (CMIST) rather than diagnoses?","answer":"Function captures who actually needs help and how (e.g., anyone who can't self-evacuate), across many diagnoses and situations, making planning equitable and practical.","category":"CMIST"},{"id":"c10_fc15","question":"What is continuity of operations?","answer":"Keeping essential services running during a disaster and restoring the rest — a core part of surge and recovery planning.","category":"Recovery"},{"id":"c10_fc16","question":"When is a disaster response truly 'over'?","answer":"Not when the last acute casualty is treated, but when the community and its responders have recovered — including after-action review feeding back into preparedness.","category":"Recovery"}]}},"quizzes":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","questions":[{"id":"c01_q01","question":"Which statement best defines a disaster from a health-system perspective?","options":["A. Any event involving more than 100 casualties","B. An event in which needs exceed the immediately available resources","C. Any weather-related emergency","D. An event declared by the federal government"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The health-system definition centers on the imbalance between needs and resources. Casualty counts, weather, or declarations do not define it — a small event can be a disaster where resources are scarce.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q02","question":"What is the correct order of the four phases of the disaster cycle?","options":["A. Response, Recovery, Mitigation, Preparedness","B. Mitigation, Preparedness, Response, Recovery","C. Preparedness, Mitigation, Recovery, Response","D. Detection, Response, Recovery, Review"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The classic cycle runs Mitigation → Preparedness → Response → Recovery, then feeds back into mitigation for the next event.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q03","question":"Installing flood barriers and enforcing seismic building codes are examples of which phase?","options":["A. Response","B. Recovery","C. Mitigation","D. Triage"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Mitigation comprises actions taken to reduce the impact of future events — structural and policy measures like barriers and building codes.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q04","question":"The PRE-DISASTER Paradigm emphasizes which pre-event elements?","options":["A. Planning and practice, resilience, and education and training","B. Triage, treatment, and transport","C. Detection and evacuation","D. Response and recovery only"],"correct":0,"rationale":"PRE-DISASTER frames readiness before an event: exercised plans, resilient people and infrastructure, and competency-based education such as the NDLS courses.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q05","question":"How do care priorities change in a disaster compared with daily emergency care?","options":["A. They do not change","B. From maximal care for each individual to the greatest good for the greatest number","C. From triage to first-come, first-served","D. All patients receive identical care"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Disaster care allocates limited resources to benefit the most patients. Triage, deferred care, and abbreviated documentation follow from this shift.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q06","question":"Why does the same tornado count as a disaster for a rural hospital but not for a metropolitan trauma system?","options":["A. Because tornado severity varies by region","B. Because the definition depends on the balance between needs and locally available resources","C. Because rural hospitals use different triage colors","D. Because federal declarations differ"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Disaster is relative to resources: casualties that overwhelm a small facility may be absorbed routinely by a large system.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q07","question":"What is the purpose of the all-hazards approach?","options":["A. To write a unique plan for every conceivable event","B. To use one common management framework across all disaster types, with hazard-specific annexes","C. To focus planning only on the most likely hazard","D. To eliminate the need for training"],"correct":1,"rationale":"All-hazards planning builds one flexible framework that applies to natural, explosive, chemical, biological, and radiological events, supplemented by specific annexes — more robust and efficient than separate plans.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q08","question":"A hospital's disaster plan is thorough but has never been exercised. What is the main risk?","options":["A. None — a written plan is sufficient","B. The plan will fail under stress because gaps were never revealed and staff lack practiced roles","C. The plan will expire legally","D. Exercises are only for EMS agencies"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Exercising is what converts paper plans into performance: it exposes gaps, builds familiarity, and creates the muscle memory needed during a real response.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q09","question":"Which is a component of a responder's personal preparedness?","options":["A. A family communication plan and go-kit","B. Memorizing every federal regulation","C. Owning specialized rescue vehicles","D. Avoiding disaster training to stay flexible"],"correct":0,"rationale":"Personal preparedness — communication plan, go-kit, dependent care arrangements, knowledge of workplace roles — keeps responders able to report for duty.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q10","question":"Why is staff personal preparedness a facility-level concern?","options":["A. It is not — it is purely private","B. Surge capacity depends on staff reporting for duty, and staff with unprepared families often cannot","C. It reduces insurance premiums","D. It replaces the need for a hospital plan"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A hospital's surge plan assumes staff availability. Personal and family readiness directly affects whether the workforce shows up in a crisis.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q11","question":"A mass-casualty incident (MCI) is best defined as:","options":["A. Any incident with fatalities","B. An event producing more patients than local resources can manage using routine procedures","C. An incident involving hazardous materials","D. Any incident requiring more than one ambulance"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The MCI definition parallels the disaster definition: patient load beyond what routine local procedures can handle.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q12","question":"During a disaster response, a provider is asked to work in a role outside their usual daily assignment, under incident command. This is:","options":["A. A violation of disaster principles","B. An expected feature of disaster response within the command structure","C. Only allowed for physicians","D. Evidence of a failed plan"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Disasters routinely require flexible role assignment under incident command; preparing providers for this shift is part of BDLS training.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q13","question":"Which activity belongs to the RECOVERY phase?","options":["A. Field triage of casualties","B. Restoring health-system function and community services after the event, potentially over years","C. Stockpiling supplies before an event","D. Building levees"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Recovery restores the community and health system to normal or improved function. Triage is response; stockpiling is preparedness; levees are mitigation.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q14","question":"Immunization campaigns that reduce a community's vulnerability to epidemics are an example of:","options":["A. Response","B. Mitigation","C. Triage","D. Evacuation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Reducing the future impact of a hazard — including biological hazards — is mitigation.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c01_q15","question":"Health professionals converging on a disaster scene without being requested or integrated into incident command are:","options":["A. Always helpful","B. A known hazard — self-dispatched responders complicate scene management and safety","C. Required by law","D. The preferred staffing method"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Spontaneous, unintegrated responders burden scene safety, accountability, and coordination. Responding through the system — when requested, into an assigned role — is the professional standard.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q16","question":"Which best captures why mitigation and preparedness 'save more lives than response'?","options":["A. Response is unimportant","B. Pre-event actions shrink the needs-versus-resources gap before it opens, preventing casualties that no response could later recover","C. Responders are usually unavailable","D. It is a slogan without basis"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Codes that keep buildings standing, plans that speed evacuation, and trained staff prevent deaths outright; even a perfect response can only salvage what the event has already done.","difficulty":"Hard"}]},"c02":{"chapter":"c02","questions":[{"id":"c02_q01","question":"What does the 'D' in the DISASTER Paradigm stand for?","options":["A. Decontamination","B. Detection","C. Defibrillation","D. Documentation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The paradigm begins with Detection — recognizing that an event's needs exceed available resources.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q02","question":"Which is the correct order of the DISASTER Paradigm components?","options":["A. Triage, Detection, Safety, Command, Support, Hazards, Evacuation, Recovery","B. Detection, Incident command, Safety and security, Assess hazards, Support, Triage and treatment, Evacuation, Recovery","C. Detection, Safety, Triage, Command, Hazards, Support, Recovery, Evacuation","D. Incident command, Detection, Triage, Evacuation, Safety, Support, Hazards, Recovery"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The ordered checklist is Detection → Incident command → Safety and security → Assess hazards → Support → Triage and treatment → Evacuation → Recovery.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q03","question":"You are the first trained responder at a building collapse with many casualties. After sizing up the scene, what comes next?","options":["A. Begin treating the nearest casualty","B. Establish and announce incident command","C. Start evacuating patients to the closest hospital","D. Wait for a supervisor before doing anything"],"correct":1,"rationale":"After detection, the first trained responder establishes incident command, creating a coordination point; command transfers later as senior officers arrive. Patient care before command and safety leads to chaos.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q04","question":"What is the correct safety priority order at a disaster scene?","options":["A. Patients, bystanders, team, self","B. Self, team, public/bystanders, patients","C. Team, patients, self, public","D. There is no priority order"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Protect yourself first, then your team, then the public, then patients — an injured rescuer consumes resources instead of providing them.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q05","question":"At a bombing scene, hazard assessment must specifically consider:","options":["A. Only the original blast site","B. Secondary devices deliberately targeting responders","C. Weather forecasts for next week","D. Hospital bed counts"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Intentional events may include secondary devices timed to strike responders — a core reason hazard assessment is continuous and staging discipline matters.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q06","question":"Why should resource support be requested early in an incident?","options":["A. To impress command","B. Because resources arrive with a delay — order for the incident you will have, not the one you see","C. Because requests expire","D. It should actually be requested last"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Mutual aid, supplies, and transport all take time to arrive. Anticipatory requests keep resources flowing in phase with the incident's growth.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q07","question":"Which transport decision best reflects disaster evacuation principles?","options":["A. Send all 40 casualties to the nearest hospital","B. Distribute casualties by severity across multiple appropriate receiving facilities","C. Transport only the walking wounded","D. Hold all patients on scene until every one is fully stabilized"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Dumping every casualty on the closest hospital recreates the disaster inside it. Command distributes patients by acuity and capability across the system.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q08","question":"Clusters of patients with similar unusual symptoms appearing at several EDs across a city over two days most likely represents:","options":["A. Coincidence requiring no action","B. The detection phase of an insidious (possibly biological/chemical) event","C. A staffing problem","D. Normal seasonal variation always"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Covert releases and epidemics announce themselves as syndromic clusters. Recognizing them as a detection signal — and notifying public health — triggers the response system.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c02_q09","question":"A physician bypasses the incident command post and begins directing ambulances personally. This behavior is:","options":["A. Ideal physician leadership","B. Freelancing — it breaks unified coordination and accountability","C. Required by medical ethics","D. The definition of unified command"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Acting outside the command structure (freelancing) fragments the operation, duplicates or contradicts orders, and endangers the responder. Clinical skills are contributed inside assigned roles.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q10","question":"When should recovery activities begin?","options":["A. Only after the scene is fully closed","B. During the response itself","C. One year after the event","D. Never — recovery is not a responder concern"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Recovery starts during response: restoring systems, tracking patients, supporting responders and survivors, and documenting lessons learned.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q11","question":"The first radio report from the initial responder at an MCI should communicate:","options":["A. A complete list of patient names","B. Estimated casualty count, hazards, resources needed, and that command is established","C. Only the responder's unit number","D. The names of the deceased"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The early size-up report paints the detection picture and mobilizes the system: casualties, hazards, needs, and command status.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q12","question":"Which action violates the Safety and security component?","options":["A. Staging until the scene is declared safe","B. Entering an unstable collapsed structure alone to reach a casualty faster","C. Wearing appropriate PPE","D. Establishing a perimeter"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Entering an uncleared, unstable structure alone risks converting a rescuer into a casualty — the exact failure the safety hierarchy exists to prevent.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q13","question":"In the DISASTER Paradigm, triage and treatment are performed using:","options":["A. First-come, first-served order","B. A standardized method (SALT) serving the greatest good for the greatest number","C. Alphabetical order","D. Insurance status"],"correct":1,"rationale":"BDLS teaches SALT, the CDC-sponsored national standard, to sort casualties so limited resources produce the most total benefit.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q14","question":"Why is hazard assessment described as continuous rather than one-time?","options":["A. To create paperwork","B. Scenes evolve — collapse, fire spread, aftershocks, or secondary devices can appear after arrival","C. Because the first assessment is always wrong","D. It is actually one-time"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The hazard picture changes: what was safe on arrival may become lethal. Continuous reassessment protects responders throughout the operation.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q15","question":"Which pairing of paradigm component and action is correct?","options":["A. Support — establishing a perimeter","B. Evacuation — distributing patients to appropriate facilities","C. Detection — providing definitive care","D. Recovery — initial scene size-up"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Evacuation covers moving the right patient to the right destination. Perimeters are safety/security; size-up is detection; definitive care follows triage/treatment.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q16","question":"The DISASTER Paradigm applies to which events?","options":["A. Only explosions","B. Only natural disasters","C. All hazards — floods, bombings, epidemics, chemical and radiological events alike","D. Only declared federal disasters"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The paradigm is BDLS's all-hazards checklist: the same ordered priorities regardless of the event's cause.","difficulty":"Easy"}]},"c03":{"chapter":"c03","questions":[{"id":"c03_q01","question":"Which are the five major functional sections of ICS?","options":["A. Command, Operations, Planning, Logistics, Finance/Administration","B. Triage, Treatment, Transport, Staging, Morgue","C. Police, Fire, EMS, Hospital, Public Health","D. Detection, Safety, Support, Evacuation, Recovery"],"correct":0,"rationale":"ICS organizes all incident work into Command, Operations, Planning, Logistics, and Finance/Administration.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q02","question":"Field triage, treatment, and transport belong to which ICS section?","options":["A. Planning","B. Operations","C. Logistics","D. Finance/Administration"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Operations performs the tactical, hands-on work of the response, including all patient-care activities.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q03","question":"Obtaining ventilators, food for responders, and portable radios is the job of:","options":["A. Command","B. Operations","C. Logistics","D. Planning"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Logistics acquires the resources the response needs — supplies, facilities, communications, and responder support.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q04","question":"What is the recommended ICS span of control?","options":["A. 1–2 direct reports","B. About 3–7 (optimally ~5)","C. 10–15","D. Unlimited"],"correct":1,"rationale":"One supervisor should directly manage roughly 3–7 people, classically 5. Larger spans trigger subdivision of the structure.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q05","question":"A hazmat incident involves fire, police, EMS, and an environmental agency, each with legal authority. The best command arrangement is:","options":["A. Four separate command posts","B. Unified command — agencies share objectives under one plan with a single Operations section","C. Whoever arrived first commands alone forever","D. No command until the state arrives"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Unified command lets multiple jurisdictions/disciplines jointly command while preserving one coordinated plan — the fix for competing command posts.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q06","question":"Which ICS role can immediately halt an unsafe operation?","options":["A. Public information officer","B. Safety officer","C. Finance chief","D. Staging manager"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The safety officer, part of the command staff, holds authority to stop any operation posing imminent danger.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q07","question":"What is NIMS?","options":["A. A hospital bed-tracking software","B. The national doctrine standardizing incident management — ICS, resource typing, credentialing, mutual aid, EOCs","C. A triage algorithm","D. A federal response team"],"correct":1,"rationale":"NIMS standardizes how all agencies and levels of government manage incidents so systems interoperate — ICS is its on-scene management component.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q08","question":"During a hospital disaster activation, a nurse receives conflicting instructions from her everyday manager and her assigned incident supervisor. Per ICS, she should:","options":["A. Follow her everyday manager","B. Follow her assigned incident supervisor — unity of command","C. Follow whichever instruction is easier","D. Do both"],"correct":1,"rationale":"ICS unity of command means each person reports to exactly one incident supervisor during the response, regardless of daily reporting lines.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q09","question":"What must occur when command is transferred to a more senior officer?","options":["A. Nothing — it is automatic","B. A formal briefing of the incoming commander and an announcement to all","C. A written exam","D. Approval from the hospital CEO"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Command transfer requires a briefing (situation, resources, plan) and notification so every responder knows who now commands.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q10","question":"The incident action plan is produced by which section?","options":["A. Planning","B. Operations","C. Logistics","D. Command staff only"],"correct":0,"rationale":"Planning collects information, tracks resources and the situation, and prepares the incident action plan for command approval.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q11","question":"An Emergency Operations Center (EOC) primarily:","options":["A. Replaces the on-scene incident commander","B. Coordinates off-scene support — resources, information, and policy — for incident command","C. Performs field triage","D. Is only activated for federal disasters"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The EOC supports and coordinates from off-scene; it does not take over tactical command of the incident.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c03_q12","question":"In hospital incident command (e.g., HICS), a job action sheet is:","options":["A. A billing document","B. A role card defining the incident duties, reporting line, and tasks for an assigned position","C. A triage tag","D. A federal form"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Job action sheets translate the ICS structure into concrete role instructions so staff can step into incident positions quickly.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q13","question":"A treatment group supervisor now directly manages 12 providers and is overwhelmed. The ICS-correct fix is:","options":["A. Work harder","B. Subdivide — create additional units/leaders to restore a 3–7 span of control","C. Remove the supervisor","D. Ignore it — span of control is advisory"],"correct":1,"rationale":"ICS is modular: when span of control exceeds ~7, the structure subdivides so every supervisor manages a workable number.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q14","question":"Why does ICS insist on common terminology (plain language, no codes)?","options":["A. Tradition","B. So responders from different agencies understand each other without translation errors","C. To shorten radio traffic","D. To comply with billing rules"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Agencies have different internal codes; plain, common terminology prevents dangerous misunderstandings in multi-agency operations.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q15","question":"Which statement about ICS scalability is TRUE?","options":["A. Every incident must activate all five sections fully","B. ICS expands and contracts modularly — small incidents may need only an incident commander","C. ICS applies only to incidents with over 100 casualties","D. Sections cannot be combined"],"correct":1,"rationale":"ICS is modular: functions are activated only as needed, growing with the incident and demobilizing as it resolves.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q16","question":"A physician arrives at a hospital disaster and begins working wherever she sees need, without checking in. The ICS problem is:","options":["A. None — initiative is always good","B. No check-in means no accountability, no assigned supervisor, and broken resource tracking","C. Physicians are exempt from ICS","D. She should have gone to the EOC"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Check-in establishes accountability and puts responders into the structure with a defined role and supervisor; unassigned helpers are untracked and can be unsafe.","difficulty":"Hard"}]},"c04":{"chapter":"c04","questions":[{"id":"c04_q01","question":"What does SALT stand for?","options":["A. Safety, Airway, Lifting, Transport","B. Sort, Assess, Lifesaving interventions, Treatment and/or transport","C. Scene, Alert, Look, Treat","D. Stabilize, Assess, Load, Triage"],"correct":1,"rationale":"SALT — Sort, Assess, Lifesaving interventions, Treatment and/or transport — is the CDC-sponsored standardized mass-casualty triage method taught in BDLS.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q02","question":"In the global sort, casualties who walk to the designated area are assessed:","options":["A. First","B. Second","C. Last","D. Never"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Walkers demonstrate perfusion, airway, and the ability to follow commands, so they receive the lowest individual-assessment priority — but they are still assessed.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q03","question":"Which casualties are assessed FIRST after global sorting?","options":["A. Those who walked","B. Those who waved","C. Those who are still or have obvious life threats (e.g., massive bleeding)","D. Those who talk loudest"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Still casualties and those with obvious life threats have the highest probability of needing immediate lifesaving intervention, so they are assessed first.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q04","question":"Which is a permitted lifesaving intervention DURING SALT triage?","options":["A. Splinting a femur fracture","B. Applying a tourniquet to massive extremity hemorrhage","C. Full spinal immobilization","D. Starting an IV infusion"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Triage-phase interventions take only seconds: hemorrhage control, airway positioning (child: consider 2 breaths), chest decompression, auto-injector antidotes. Splints, IVs, and immobilization wait for the treatment phase.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q05","question":"An adult casualty is not breathing after you open the airway. In SALT, this casualty is categorized as:","options":["A. Immediate","B. Expectant","C. Dead","D. Delayed"],"correct":2,"rationale":"An apneic adult after airway opening is Dead (black) in mass-casualty triage; CPR for one arrest would consume resources needed by many salvageable casualties.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q06","question":"How does SALT modify the apnea assessment for a child?","options":["A. No difference from adults","B. Consider giving 2 rescue breaths after opening the airway; if breathing does not resume, the child is Dead","C. Perform 10 minutes of CPR","D. All apneic children are Expectant"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Because pediatric arrest is usually hypoxic, SALT allows consideration of two rescue breaths for an apneic child — a seconds-long intervention that can restore breathing.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q07","question":"A breathing casualty obeys commands, has a radial pulse, no respiratory distress, controlled bleeding, and only abrasions. Category?","options":["A. Immediate","B. Delayed","C. Minimal","D. Expectant"],"correct":2,"rationale":"All assessment questions are 'yes' and the injuries are minor — Minimal (green).","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q08","question":"A breathing casualty obeys commands, has a pulse, no distress, controlled hemorrhage — but has an obviously fractured femur. Category?","options":["A. Minimal","B. Delayed","C. Immediate","D. Dead"],"correct":1,"rationale":"All questions 'yes' with significant (but not immediately life-threatening) injuries = Delayed (yellow).","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q09","question":"A casualty is breathing but does not obey commands and has no radial pulse. Resources are adequate for prompt care. Category?","options":["A. Minimal","B. Delayed","C. Immediate","D. Expectant"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Any 'no' answer with a reasonable chance of survival given current resources = Immediate (red) — top priority for treatment and transport.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q10","question":"What does the Expectant (gray) category signify?","options":["A. The casualty is deceased","B. Alive, but survival unlikely with currently available resources; provide comfort care and re-triage if resources improve","C. The casualty refused care","D. Minor injuries only"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Expectant is a resource-driven category, not abandonment: comfort care is given, and the patient is upgraded if the resource picture changes.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q11","question":"Why is mass-casualty triage repeated at multiple stages (re-triage)?","options":["A. Regulatory paperwork","B. Because patients deteriorate or improve and resources change over time","C. To keep responders busy","D. It is not repeated"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Triage is a snapshot with incomplete data. Re-triage at the treatment area, before transport, and at hospital arrival catches deterioration and allows upgrades.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q12","question":"The fundamental goal of mass-casualty triage is to:","options":["A. Give every patient maximal individual care","B. Produce the greatest number of survivors with the available resources","C. Transport patients in order of arrival","D. Identify patients for research"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Triage rations limited resources to maximize total survival — a deliberate departure from everyday maximal individual care.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q13","question":"A triage officer stops to splint fractures and bandage minor wounds during the assessment pass. The problem is:","options":["A. None — treatment is always good","B. Triage halts for everyone not yet sorted; only seconds-long lifesaving interventions belong in the triage pass","C. Splinting requires physician orders","D. Bandaging is a logistics function"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The triage officer's job is sorting the whole scene. Prolonged care during triage leaves unsorted casualties — possibly Immediate ones — undiscovered.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q14","question":"Which casualty is at greatest risk of being mishandled by an untrained crowd-driven response?","options":["A. The loudly screaming walking wounded","B. The silent, still casualty who cannot call for help","C. The casualty with a minor laceration","D. The bystander"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Noise attracts attention, but the still and silent are often the most critical — which is why SALT assesses them first.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q15","question":"More ambulances and a second trauma team arrive. What should happen to Expectant-category patients?","options":["A. Nothing — categories are final","B. Re-triage them; with more resources some may now be Immediate","C. Move them to the morgue","D. Discharge them"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Expectant is defined relative to available resources. When resources improve, re-triage can and should upgrade salvageable patients.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c04_q16","question":"A casualty walked to the green area, but 20 minutes later is pale, tachycardic, and confused. What does this demonstrate?","options":["A. Walking wounded never deteriorate","B. The need for ongoing assessment and re-triage — green patients can harbor evolving internal injuries","C. The initial sort was illegal","D. The patient should be moved to Dead"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The global sort is a first pass, not a clearance. Occult injuries (e.g., internal hemorrhage) evolve — monitoring and re-triage of the green area is mandatory.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c04_q17","question":"Auto-injector antidotes given during the SALT lifesaving-intervention step are most relevant to which event type?","options":["A. Earthquake","B. Nerve-agent / organophosphate chemical exposure","C. Flood","D. Heat wave"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Antidote auto-injectors (e.g., for nerve agents) are seconds-long, potentially lifesaving triage interventions in chemical events.","difficulty":"Medium"}]},"c05":{"chapter":"c05","questions":[{"id":"c05_q01","question":"What is the leading cause of death in floods and hurricanes?","options":["A. Electrocution","B. Drowning, often vehicle-related","C. Building collapse","D. Lightning"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Most flood/hurricane deaths are drownings, and a large share involve vehicles driven into floodwater — hence 'turn around, don't drown.'","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q02","question":"A family presents after a storm with headache, nausea, and confusion. Their power is out and a generator runs in the garage. Most likely diagnosis?","options":["A. Food poisoning","B. Carbon monoxide poisoning","C. Heat stroke","D. Influenza"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Indoor/attached-space generator use after outages is the classic post-storm CO scenario: nonspecific symptoms in multiple household members.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q03","question":"Crush syndrome after release of a compressed limb is driven by:","options":["A. Air embolism","B. Reperfusion washout of potassium, myoglobin, and acids from damaged muscle","C. Fat embolism only","D. Anaphylaxis"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Releasing compression flushes muscle breakdown products into the circulation: hyperkalemia (dysrhythmias), myoglobinuric renal injury, acidosis, and shock.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q04","question":"For a casualty entrapped under rubble for 3 hours, when should aggressive IV fluids ideally begin?","options":["A. After hospital arrival","B. Before the compression is released","C. Only if urine output falls","D. Fluids are contraindicated"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Pre-release volume loading protects the kidneys and blunts the reperfusion insult; release without preparation risks sudden hyperkalemic arrest and shock.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q05","question":"The most dangerous immediate complication at the moment of extrication of a prolonged crush patient is:","options":["A. Wound infection","B. Hyperkalemic dysrhythmia and cardiovascular collapse","C. Tetanus","D. Kidney stones"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The potassium surge at reperfusion can cause immediate fatal dysrhythmias — the reason for pre-release fluids and monitoring.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q06","question":"The characteristic tornado injury pattern is:","options":["A. Drowning","B. Penetrating trauma and heavily contaminated complex wounds from ballistic debris","C. Pure thermal burns","D. Radiation sickness"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Tornadoes accelerate debris to ballistic speeds, producing penetrating injuries and soil-contaminated wounds concentrated along the damage path.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q07","question":"Heat stroke is distinguished from heat exhaustion by:","options":["A. Sweating","B. Altered mental status with severe hyperthermia","C. Thirst","D. Muscle cramps"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Central nervous system dysfunction (confusion, seizures, coma) with hyperthermia defines heat stroke — a true emergency demanding immediate active cooling.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q08","question":"The correct prehospital priority for heat stroke is:","options":["A. Transport first, cool at hospital","B. Rapid active cooling started immediately, continued during transport","C. Oral rehydration only","D. Antipyretics like acetaminophen"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Outcome tracks time above critical temperature — cool first (ice-water immersion where feasible) and keep cooling en route. Antipyretics do not work for environmental hyperthermia.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q09","question":"Which population is at highest risk of dying in a heat wave?","options":["A. Young athletes only","B. Elderly, isolated people without cooling, and those on thermoregulation-impairing medications","C. Office workers","D. Children in schools"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Heat-wave mortality concentrates among the isolated elderly and chronically ill, who decompensate quietly at home — a case for community outreach during events.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q10","question":"What continuing hazard specifically threatens rescuers during earthquake response?","options":["A. Lightning","B. Aftershocks causing further collapse","C. Storm surge","D. Hail"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Aftershocks can drop already-weakened structures onto rescuers — hazard assessment must be continuous and entry decisions disciplined.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q11","question":"Wounds sustained in floodwater should be treated as:","options":["A. Clean","B. Contaminated — high infection risk, aggressive cleaning, tetanus review","C. Requiring no follow-up","D. Immediately sutured without irrigation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Floodwater carries sewage, chemicals, and debris; wounds are contaminated with elevated infection risk, warranting thorough cleansing and tetanus prophylaxis review.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q12","question":"Two weeks after a hurricane, EDs remain over capacity. The MOST likely driver is:","options":["A. Ongoing storm trauma","B. Decompensated chronic disease — lost medications, dialysis, oxygen, and power-dependent devices","C. Tourist injuries","D. Insurance visits"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The medical surge outlasts the trauma surge: chronic conditions decompensate when the care infrastructure fails — a planning target often missed.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q13","question":"Fever clusters appearing in a crowded post-disaster shelter should prompt:","options":["A. No action — fevers are expected","B. Outbreak evaluation, isolation measures, and public-health notification","C. Closing the shelter immediately without assessment","D. Antibiotics for everyone"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Crowded shelters breed respiratory and gastrointestinal outbreaks; clusters demand evaluation, infection-control measures, and health-department involvement.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q14","question":"Which pairing of hazard and signature is correct?","options":["A. Flood — crush syndrome","B. Earthquake — entrapment with crush injury","C. Tornado — drowning","D. Heat wave — penetrating debris trauma"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Earthquakes produce structural collapse with entrapment and crush. Floods drown, tornadoes shred with debris, heat waves cook.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q15","question":"Why does knowing a hazard's signature matter operationally?","options":["A. It is academic trivia","B. It lets command anticipate casualty types, request the right support, and warn hospitals before patients arrive","C. It replaces triage","D. It only matters for documentation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Signatures convert hazard type into predicted needs — burn beds, dialysis, pediatric capability — driving the Support component of the DISASTER Paradigm early.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c05_q16","question":"A rescued crush patient develops dark tea-colored urine. This indicates:","options":["A. Normal dehydration","B. Myoglobinuria — muscle pigment threatening the kidneys; aggressive fluids and renal protection needed","C. Bladder infection","D. Dietary cause"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Dark urine after crush = myoglobin from ruptured muscle. Untreated it precipitates acute kidney injury; management centers on volume expansion.","difficulty":"Hard"}]},"c06":{"chapter":"c06","questions":[{"id":"c06_q01","question":"Injury caused directly by the blast pressure wave is classified as:","options":["A. Primary","B. Secondary","C. Tertiary","D. Quaternary"],"correct":0,"rationale":"Primary blast injury is caused by the overpressure wave itself, targeting air-filled organs (ears, lungs, GI tract).","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c06_q02","question":"A casualty struck by bolts and glass propelled by an explosion has which mechanism of injury?","options":["A. Primary","B. Secondary","C. Tertiary","D. Quinary"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Secondary blast injury — fragments and debris — is also the most common cause of injury and death in bombings.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c06_q03","question":"A victim thrown by the blast against a concrete pillar suffers which mechanism?","options":["A. Primary","B. Secondary","C. Tertiary","D. Quaternary"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Tertiary injury results from bodily displacement — being thrown against objects or the ground.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c06_q04","question":"Radiological material packed around an explosive ('dirty bomb') produces which class of injury?","options":["A. Quaternary","B. Quinary","C. Primary","D. Tertiary"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Quinary injuries come from additives to the device — radiological, chemical, or biological contaminants.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q05","question":"Which organs are most vulnerable to the primary blast wave?","options":["A. Solid organs — liver and spleen","B. Air-filled organs — ears, lungs, GI tract","C. Bones","D. Skin"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The pressure wave does its work at air-tissue interfaces: tympanic membranes, alveoli, and bowel.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c06_q06","question":"A blast survivor from inside a bus develops dyspnea, falling SpO2, and hemoptysis 2 hours later. Most likely diagnosis?","options":["A. Anxiety","B. Blast lung (primary pulmonary blast injury)","C. Simple rib fracture","D. Asthma"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Enclosed-space blast plus delayed respiratory deterioration with hemoptysis is classic blast lung — pulmonary contusion and alveolar disruption that can present hours after exposure.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q07","question":"When ventilating a patient with suspected blast lung, the provider should:","options":["A. Use maximal pressures to recruit the lungs","B. Use the lowest effective pressures and monitor for pneumothorax and air embolism","C. Avoid oxygen","D. Hyperventilate at 30 breaths/min"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Positive pressure can extend alveolar rupture, causing tension pneumothorax or arterial air embolism — gentle ventilation is the rule.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q08","question":"An intact tympanic membrane after a blast means:","options":["A. No primary blast injury occurred","B. Other primary blast injuries (lung, GI) are still possible — TM status is not a reliable rule-out","C. The patient can be discharged immediately","D. The blast was small"],"correct":1,"rationale":"TM rupture is the most common primary injury, but its absence does not exclude blast lung or GI injury — clinical assessment and observation still apply.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q09","question":"Why do enclosed-space explosions cause worse primary blast injury?","options":["A. Less oxygen indoors","B. Reflected pressure waves multiply the blast dose delivered to victims","C. Victims are older indoors","D. They do not — open air is worse"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Walls reflect and re-reflect the pressure wave, so victims receive multiple wave exposures, raising primary injury incidence and severity.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q10","question":"Minutes after a downtown bombing, the nearest ED receives 25 walking wounded. What should hospital command anticipate?","options":["A. The event is over — these are all the casualties","B. The critical casualties will arrive later (30–60 min) by EMS; capacity must be reserved for that second wave","C. No more patients will come","D. Only pediatric patients will follow"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Bombing arrivals are 'upside-down': self-transporting minor casualties come first, while the critical ones — needing extrication and EMS — arrive later into an already-crowded ED unless capacity is protected.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q11","question":"The greatest cause of PREVENTABLE death in blast and penetrating mass casualties is:","options":["A. Head injury","B. Uncontrolled extremity hemorrhage","C. Burns","D. Hearing loss"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Extremity exsanguination is rapidly fatal and rapidly fixable — early tourniquets (including bystander Stop the Bleed response) save the most salvageable lives.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c06_q12","question":"At a confirmed intentional bombing, EMS should initially:","options":["A. Rush straight to the epicenter","B. Stage until law enforcement addresses secondary devices, then operate under unified command","C. Ignore law enforcement","D. Wait 24 hours"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Secondary devices target responders. Staging, perimeter control, and unified command with law enforcement precede casualty care in the hot area.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c06_q13","question":"A blast survivor suddenly develops focal weakness and then collapses. A key blast-specific cause to consider is:","options":["A. Arterial air embolism from disrupted alveoli","B. Simple faint","C. Dehydration","D. Migraine"],"correct":0,"rationale":"Alveolar disruption can admit air into pulmonary veins and the arterial circulation, causing stroke-like deficits, myocardial ischemia, or sudden death.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c06_q14","question":"Burns, crush from structural collapse, and smoke inhalation at a bombing are classified as:","options":["A. Primary","B. Secondary","C. Tertiary","D. Quaternary"],"correct":3,"rationale":"Quaternary covers all explosion-related injuries not in the first three classes — burns, crush, inhalation, and exacerbated chronic disease.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q15","question":"During the warm-zone phase of an active-violence response, the care priority is:","options":["A. Full trauma workups","B. Rapid hemorrhage control (tourniquets/packing) before movement to the cold zone","C. Detailed documentation","D. Psychological counseling"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Phased care: suppress threat (hot), control life-threatening bleeding with seconds-long interventions (warm), full care once in the cold zone.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q16","question":"Which blast casualty most needs prolonged observation despite looking well?","options":["A. A bystander 500 m away with no symptoms","B. A survivor from within the enclosed blast space with ringing ears but normal vitals","C. A responder who arrived after detonation","D. A patient with an isolated small hand laceration from 200 m away"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Significant (especially enclosed-space) exposure risks delayed blast lung and GI injury; TM symptoms mark real wave exposure. Observation catches the late presenters.","difficulty":"Hard"}]},"c07":{"chapter":"c07","questions":[{"id":"c07_q01","question":"Multiple people collapse within minutes at a transit station; several have pinpoint pupils and copious secretions. Bystanders report a strange odor. The FIRST responder priority is:","options":["A. Rush in and start treating","B. Stage uphill/upwind, avoid unprotected entry, and establish zones — this is a chemical scene","C. Begin CPR on the nearest victim","D. Open windows and doors"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A toxidrome cluster tied to one location is a chemical release until proven otherwise. Unprotected entry adds responders to the casualty count; staging and zoning come first.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c07_q02","question":"Pinpoint pupils, salivation, lacrimation, bronchorrhea, and muscle twitching indicate which toxidrome?","options":["A. Anticholinergic","B. Cholinergic (nerve agent/organophosphate)","C. Opioid","D. Sympathomimetic"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Acetylcholinesterase inhibition floods synapses with acetylcholine: SLUDGE/DUMBELS muscarinic signs plus nicotinic twitching — the nerve-agent signature.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c07_q03","question":"The 'killer B's' of nerve-agent poisoning are:","options":["A. Blisters, burns, bruising","B. Bronchorrhea, bronchospasm, bradycardia","C. Bleeding, blindness, bradypnea","D. Bacteremia, botulism, burns"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Victims drown in secretions with constricted airways and a slowing heart — the lethal triad that atropine directly treats.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c07_q04","question":"How should atropine be dosed in severe nerve-agent poisoning?","options":["A. One fixed dose only","B. Titrated repeatedly until bronchial secretions dry","C. Until pupils dilate","D. Atropine is contraindicated"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The endpoint is dried secretions and ventilability — not pupil size and not a fixed maximum; severe poisonings need repeated dosing.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c07_q05","question":"Which drug pair constitutes the classic nerve-agent antidote kit?","options":["A. Naloxone and flumazenil","B. Atropine and pralidoxime (2-PAM)","C. Epinephrine and amiodarone","D. Calcium and insulin"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Atropine blocks muscarinic effects; pralidoxime reactivates acetylcholinesterase — packaged together in auto-injectors, with benzodiazepines for seizures.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c07_q06","question":"What proportion-level of contamination is removed by clothing removal alone?","options":["A. Almost none","B. A large majority of it","C. Exactly 10%","D. Clothing removal spreads contamination"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Disrobing eliminates a large majority of contamination in seconds — the fastest, highest-yield decon step, done before water.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c07_q07","question":"A casualty is covered in a dry powdered agent. Before water flushing, you should:","options":["A. Apply lotion","B. Brush off the powder first","C. Wrap the patient in plastic","D. Nothing — go straight to water"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Some dry agents react with water; brushing removes the bulk safely before copious irrigation.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c07_q08","question":"Decontamination takes place in which zone?","options":["A. Hot zone","B. Warm zone","C. Cold zone","D. Green zone"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The warm zone is the decon corridor between the contaminated hot zone and the clean cold zone where treatment occurs.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c07_q09","question":"A soaked, symptomatic patient from a liquid nerve-agent release needs antidote. The correct sequencing principle is:","options":["A. Full treatment first, decon later","B. Gross decon (clothing off, flush) with antidote auto-injector during triage — decon and lifesaving interventions go hand in hand, and antidotes cannot outrun ongoing absorption","C. Wait for hospital arrival for both","D. Decon can be skipped for nerve agents"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Continued skin absorption defeats antidotes. SALT permits auto-injectors during triage, but gross decon of liquid exposure is itself lifesaving and must not wait.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c07_q10","question":"Mustard (vesicant) exposure typically presents:","options":["A. Immediately with blisters","B. After a delay of hours — skin, eye, and airway injury declare late","C. Never symptomatically","D. Only with pinpoint pupils"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Mustard's cellular damage is immediate but clinical effects are classically delayed hours — casualties may leave the scene before blistering starts, so exposure history matters.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c07_q11","question":"A worker exposed to phosgene feels better after initial eye/throat irritation. The key risk is:","options":["A. None — recovery is complete","B. Delayed pulmonary edema hours later — observation is required","C. Immediate paralysis","D. Blistering of the skin"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Phosgene classically causes delayed non-cardiogenic pulmonary edema after a deceptive latent period; 'improved' patients still need observation.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c07_q12","question":"Several firefighters collapse after an enclosed-space fire; they are comatose with normal pulse oximetry readings. A key consideration is:","options":["A. Cyanide toxicity — treat with hydroxocobalamin","B. Simple exhaustion","C. Vesicant exposure","D. Riot-control agent"],"correct":0,"rationale":"Combustion of synthetics releases cyanide, which blocks cellular oxygen use — collapse with deceptively normal SpO2. Hydroxocobalamin is the preferred antidote.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c07_q13","question":"Which agent class has NO specific antidote, relying on decon, oxygen, and supportive care?","options":["A. Nerve agents","B. Pulmonary/choking agents and vesicants","C. Cyanide","D. Opioids"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Chlorine, phosgene, and blister agents are managed supportively — no antidote exists; decon and respiratory support are the treatment.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c07_q14","question":"An undeconned, visibly wet casualty is driven by bystanders to the ED doors. The correct facility action is:","options":["A. Bring him straight to a resuscitation bay","B. Intercept and decon outside (clothes off, wash) before entry — protecting staff and the facility from secondary contamination","C. Refuse all care","D. Admit him and decon tomorrow"],"correct":1,"rationale":"One contaminated patient can poison staff and close the department. Hospitals must decon self-presenting casualties outside before entry — care and decon proceed together.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c07_q15","question":"Which statement about PPE and zones is correct?","options":["A. Unprotected clinicians may enter the hot zone briefly","B. Unprotected providers remain in the cold zone; hot-zone entry requires hazard-appropriate protection","C. Surgical masks suffice for hot-zone entry","D. Zones are optional at small scenes"],"correct":1,"rationale":"PPE is matched to the hazard; providers without appropriate protection work only in the cold zone. Zone discipline is what keeps rescuers from becoming casualties.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c07_q16","question":"Antidote auto-injectors during SALT triage are appropriate for:","options":["A. Every chemical casualty","B. Casualties with the nerve-agent (cholinergic) toxidrome","C. Vesicant burns","D. Riot-control agent tearing"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The triage-phase auto-injector is a seconds-long lifesaving intervention aimed at the cholinergic toxidrome; other agent classes lack injectable field antidotes.","difficulty":"Medium"}]},"c08":{"chapter":"c08","questions":[{"id":"c08_q01","question":"A covert biological release differs from most other disasters because:","options":["A. It is always announced in advance","B. Its 'scene' is a pattern of illness in the population, revealed after an incubation period","C. It causes immediate visible casualties at one location","D. It requires no public-health involvement"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Incubation periods mean a covert event surfaces as scattered illness over days; the detectors are clinicians and epidemiologists recognizing the pattern, not responders at a scene.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c08_q02","question":"Which is a Category A bioterrorism agent?","options":["A. Salmonella","B. Anthrax","C. Ricin","D. Common cold virus"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Anthrax is Category A ('A B PLoT': Anthrax, Botulism, Plague, smallpox, Tularemia, viral hemorrhagic fevers) — high mortality with special preparedness needs.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c08_q03","question":"Which set lists Category A agents?","options":["A. Anthrax, botulism, plague, smallpox, tularemia, viral hemorrhagic fevers","B. Influenza, measles, mumps, rubella","C. Salmonella, E. coli, cholera, ricin","D. HIV, hepatitis, tuberculosis, malaria"],"correct":0,"rationale":"The Category A group is anthrax, botulism, plague, smallpox, tularemia, and viral hemorrhagic fevers — the highest-priority threats.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c08_q04","question":"Which epidemiologic finding should raise suspicion of an intentional biological event?","options":["A. A few influenza cases during flu season","B. A large point-source cluster of a severe illness that is unusual for the area and season","C. One case of the common cold","D. Seasonal allergy complaints"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Point-source clusters, unusual diseases for the region/season, and unexpected severity are classic red flags for an intentional or unusual biological event.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c08_q05","question":"A patient with suspected smallpox requires which precautions?","options":["A. Contact only","B. Droplet only","C. Airborne precautions (N95+ respirator and negative-pressure room) plus contact","D. Standard precautions only"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Smallpox spreads by the airborne route (and contact with lesions), requiring a fitted respirator, negative-pressure isolation, and contact precautions.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c08_q06","question":"What is the difference between isolation and quarantine?","options":["A. They are the same","B. Isolation separates the ill; quarantine restricts the exposed-but-well","C. Isolation is for the exposed; quarantine is for the ill","D. Both apply only to responders"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Isolation applies to people who are sick; quarantine applies to people who were exposed but are not yet symptomatic.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c08_q07","question":"A clinician strongly suspects a case of inhalational anthrax. The most important early action is to:","options":["A. Wait for blood cultures before telling anyone","B. Notify public health immediately while isolating and protecting staff","C. Discharge the patient to avoid alarm","D. Treat and say nothing until three cases appear"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Early notification — before confirmation — lets public health investigate, initiate prophylaxis for others, and mount the response. Delay costs exposed people their prophylaxis window.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c08_q08","question":"Antibiotics given to people exposed to anthrax before they become ill is an example of:","options":["A. Isolation","B. Post-exposure prophylaxis","C. Quarantine","D. Crisis standards of care"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Preventive treatment of the exposed-but-well to stop disease from developing is post-exposure prophylaxis, often dispensed at PODs.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c08_q09","question":"The Strategic National Stockpile exists to:","options":["A. Store weapons","B. Supplement local medications, vaccines, and supplies during large public-health emergencies","C. Replace hospital pharmacies permanently","D. Fund research"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The SNS is a national cache deployed to bolster local resources during major events — for example, antibiotics or vaccines for mass prophylaxis.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c08_q10","question":"Which PPE is appropriate for a patient with pneumonic plague (droplet spread)?","options":["A. Airborne precautions with negative pressure","B. Droplet precautions — surgical mask within close range plus standard precautions","C. No precautions","D. Contact precautions only"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Pneumonic plague transmits by respiratory droplets at close range, so droplet precautions (surgical mask) are used — reserving airborne PPE for truly airborne agents.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c08_q11","question":"During a pandemic with constrained supplies, protecting the workforce includes:","options":["A. Removing all PPE requirements to save stock","B. PPE with conservation/extended-use strategies, vaccination, and mental-health support","C. Sending symptomatic staff to work","D. Ignoring staffing sustainability"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A months-long event depends on the workforce: appropriate PPE (with conservation when scarce), vaccination, and mental-health/sustainable-staffing measures keep responders functional.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c08_q12","question":"Non-pharmaceutical interventions (NPIs) are MOST important:","options":["A. Never — only drugs work","B. Before specific vaccines or therapeutics are available","C. Only after the pandemic ends","D. Only for responders"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Distancing, hygiene, masking, and isolation/quarantine are the primary tools to slow spread early, especially before targeted vaccines or treatments exist.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c08_q13","question":"Simultaneous outbreaks of the same unusual illness in three distant cities most strongly suggests:","options":["A. Ordinary seasonal illness","B. A possible intentional/multi-site biological release warranting public-health investigation","C. Laboratory error only","D. No cause for concern"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Geographically separate simultaneous clusters of the same rare disease are a hallmark epidemiologic clue for an intentional or point-source event.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c08_q14","question":"When the transmission route of a suspected biological agent is unknown, the safest PPE approach is to:","options":["A. Use standard precautions only","B. Default to a higher level of protection until the route is known","C. Use no PPE to avoid alarming patients","D. Wait for lab results before wearing PPE"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Uncertainty warrants higher precaution: it is safer to step down PPE once the agent/route is characterized than to under-protect against an airborne threat.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c08_q15","question":"Crisis standards of care are invoked when:","options":["A. A single patient is critically ill","B. Demand overwhelms resources, requiring formally declared allocation of scarce resources for population benefit","C. A hospital wants to reduce documentation","D. Staff prefer a simpler workflow"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Crisis standards are a declared, framework-governed shift used only when needs exceed resources, allocating scarce resources to maximize population benefit.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c08_q16","question":"Which best captures the clinician's pivotal role in a covert biological event?","options":["A. Waiting for authorities to announce the event","B. Recognizing an unusual case/pattern and reporting it early to trigger the public-health response","C. Managing the scene perimeter","D. Performing decontamination"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Because covert events surface in clinics and EDs, the alert clinician who recognizes and reports an unusual illness is frequently what starts the entire response.","difficulty":"Medium"}]},"c09":{"chapter":"c09","questions":[{"id":"c09_q01","question":"A patient stood in a radiation field but has no radioactive material on or in them. This is:","options":["A. External contamination","B. Internal contamination","C. Irradiation (exposure) — the patient is not radioactive","D. A dirty bomb injury"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Irradiation is exposure to a radiation field, like an X-ray. Once out of the field, the patient carries no radioactive material and cannot contaminate others.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c09_q02","question":"Which three principles protect responders from radiation?","options":["A. Time, distance, shielding","B. Airway, breathing, circulation","C. Detect, decon, dispose","D. Isolate, quarantine, prophylax"],"correct":0,"rationale":"Minimizing time, maximizing distance, and interposing shielding are the fundamental radiation-protection levers.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c09_q03","question":"A contaminated patient also has an obstructed airway and severe hemorrhage. What is the correct priority?","options":["A. Full decontamination before any care","B. Treat the life-threatening injuries first, then decontaminate","C. Give potassium iodide before anything else","D. Refuse care until a radiation officer arrives"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Trauma kills faster than external contamination. With standard precautions, airway and hemorrhage control come first; decon follows stabilization.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c09_q04","question":"Does standard PPE protect a responder from penetrating gamma radiation?","options":["A. Yes, completely","B. No — PPE prevents contamination but distance and shielding reduce penetrating dose","C. Only if double-gloved","D. Only N95 respirators do"],"correct":1,"rationale":"PPE stops particles from landing on skin/airway (contamination) but does not block gamma rays; time, distance, and shielding govern penetrating dose.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c09_q05","question":"A 'dirty bomb' (radiological dispersal device) causes its GREATEST immediate harm through:","options":["A. Acute radiation syndrome in everyone nearby","B. The conventional explosive blast, with contamination as a secondary and psychological threat","C. Thyroid cancer within hours","D. Internal contamination only"],"correct":1,"rationale":"An RDD's immediate casualties come from the blast; the scattered radioactive material is usually a contamination and fear problem rather than an immediate lethal radiation dose.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c09_q06","question":"In acute radiation syndrome, an earlier onset of vomiting indicates:","options":["A. A lower dose and better prognosis","B. A higher dose and worse prognosis","C. Nothing about dose","D. Internal contamination only"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Time-to-vomiting is a rapid dose surrogate: the sooner and more severe the prodromal vomiting, the higher the dose received.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c09_q07","question":"Which body system is affected first (at the lowest whole-body doses causing ARS)?","options":["A. Cardiovascular/CNS","B. Gastrointestinal","C. Hematopoietic","D. Renal"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The hematopoietic system is most radiosensitive: falling blood counts cause infection and bleeding. GI and CV/CNS syndromes appear at progressively higher doses.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c09_q08","question":"What does potassium iodide (KI) protect against?","options":["A. All radiation exposure","B. External gamma radiation","C. Thyroid uptake of radioactive iodine only","D. Blast injury"],"correct":2,"rationale":"KI saturates the thyroid to block radioiodine uptake, reducing thyroid-cancer risk. It does nothing for other radionuclides or external radiation.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c09_q09","question":"A nurse fears 'catching radiation' from a patient who was irradiated (exposed) but is not contaminated. The correct education is:","options":["A. The fear is justified — avoid the patient","B. An irradiated, non-contaminated patient is not radioactive and poses no risk, like someone who had an X-ray","C. The patient must be isolated for a week","D. Only lead aprons allow contact"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Exposure is not contamination. A person who leaves a radiation field carries no source and cannot irradiate others — a key point for calming staff and enabling care.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c09_q10","question":"The single most effective step to reduce external radiological contamination on a patient is:","options":["A. Administering KI","B. Removing the clothing","C. Giving antibiotics","D. Shaving the head"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Clothing removal eliminates the large majority of external contamination, mirroring chemical decon; gentle washing addresses the rest.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c09_q11","question":"When washing radiological contamination from intact skin and wounds, you should:","options":["A. Scrub abrasively to remove every particle","B. Wash gently with soap and water, working from wounds outward, avoiding abrasion","C. Use only alcohol","D. Avoid water entirely"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Gentle washing prevents driving contamination into the skin or wounds; working from wounds outward protects against internal contamination.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c09_q12","question":"Doubling your distance from a point radiation source affects dose how?","options":["A. Halves it","B. Reduces it dramatically (roughly to one quarter — inverse-square)","C. Has no effect","D. Doubles it"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Dose from a point source follows the inverse-square law, so doubling distance cuts dose to about one-quarter — distance is a powerful, immediate protection.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c09_q13","question":"Internal contamination occurs when radioactive material is:","options":["A. In a field around the patient","B. On the patient's clothing only","C. Taken into the body via inhalation, ingestion, or wounds","D. Detected by a monitor across the room"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Internal contamination means the material is inside the body and requires medical management, unlike external contamination (removable) or irradiation (no material present).","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c09_q14","question":"For which event is potassium iodide MOST relevant?","options":["A. A cobalt-60 external exposure","B. A release involving radioactive iodine (e.g., a reactor accident)","C. A pure blast injury","D. Any radiation event regardless of isotope"],"correct":1,"rationale":"KI is useful specifically when radioiodine is released; it blocks thyroid uptake. It is irrelevant for isotopes that are not iodine or for external exposure.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c09_q15","question":"Why is psychological/behavioral care a major component of radiological response?","options":["A. It is not important","B. Radiation fear is powerful and often exceeds the physical risk, generating worried-well surges and panic","C. Because radiation causes immediate psychosis","D. Only to reduce paperwork"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The dread associated with radiation frequently produces large worried-well surges and psychological casualties that can overwhelm systems even when physical doses are low — clear communication is essential.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c09_q16","question":"A responder is wearing full PPE near a strong sealed gamma source and feels fully protected. The flaw is:","options":["A. None — PPE is sufficient","B. PPE does not stop gamma radiation; the responder still needs to limit time, maximize distance, and use shielding","C. PPE increases the dose","D. Gamma radiation is harmless"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Contamination PPE gives a false sense of safety against penetrating gamma rays. Only time, distance, and shielding reduce that dose.","difficulty":"Medium"}]},"c10":{"chapter":"c10","questions":[{"id":"c10_q01","question":"What are the four S's of surge capacity?","options":["A. Speed, Skill, Safety, Support","B. Staff, Stuff, Space, Systems","C. Sort, Signal, Stage, Send","D. Scene, Size, Supply, Standard"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Surge capacity rests on Staff, Stuff (supplies/equipment), Space, and Systems (command, communications, tracking).","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c10_q02","question":"A hospital has doubled its bed count for a surge but has no additional nurses or physicians. What principle does this violate?","options":["A. None — beds are what matter","B. The weakest of the four S's caps the surge; without Staff, extra Space is unusable","C. Crisis standards of care","D. CMIST"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Surge is limited by its weakest pillar. Beds without staff to work them do not expand real capacity.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c10_q03","question":"Repurposing a post-anesthesia unit as extra ICU space and substituting equivalent equipment describes which level of care?","options":["A. Conventional","B. Contingency","C. Crisis","D. Normal"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Contingency care uses functionally equivalent adaptations — repurposed spaces and substituted supplies — before resources are truly overwhelmed.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c10_q04","question":"Crisis standards of care are characterized by:","options":["A. Slightly adapted but equivalent care","B. A formally declared, ethically/legally framed allocation of scarce resources for population benefit when demand overwhelms resources","C. Normal operations","D. Reduced documentation for convenience"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Crisis standards represent a deliberate, declared shift used only when needs exceed resources despite all adaptations, allocating scarce resources to maximize population benefit.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c10_q05","question":"How should a health system transition into crisis standards of care?","options":["A. Gradually and informally as things get busy","B. Deliberately and formally, under an ethical and legal framework","C. Only after a lawsuit","D. It should never be used"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Crisis standards must be entered by explicit declaration under governance frameworks, not by unplanned drift, to protect patients, providers, and fairness.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c10_q06","question":"After a terrorist bombing, an emergency department is flooded with people who have minimal or no physical injury but severe anxiety. This illustrates:","options":["A. Malingering that should be ignored","B. Psychological casualties/'worried well' — which can outnumber the physically injured and require behavioral-health capacity","C. A billing opportunity","D. A reason to close the ED"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Fear generates large numbers of psychological casualties, especially after terrorism/CBRN events; planning must include behavioral-health surge.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c10_q07","question":"Which action is part of psychological first aid?","options":["A. Requiring survivors to describe the traumatic event in detail","B. Ensuring safety and basic needs, providing calm, connecting people to loved ones, and linking to services","C. Prescribing sedatives to everyone","D. Isolating survivors from information"],"correct":1,"rationale":"PFA promotes safety, calm, connectedness, self-efficacy, and hope — and specifically does NOT force people to recount their trauma.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c10_q08","question":"What does CMIST stand for?","options":["A. Command, Medical, Incident, Safety, Transport","B. Communication, Maintaining health, Independence, Support/Safety/Self-determination, Transportation","C. Chemical, Microbial, Irradiation, Shock, Trauma","D. Contact, Mask, Isolate, Screen, Treat"],"correct":1,"rationale":"CMIST is a functional-needs framework: Communication, Maintaining health, Independence, Support/Safety/Self-determination, and Transportation.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c10_q09","question":"Why does BDLS teach planning for functional needs (CMIST) rather than by diagnosis?","options":["A. Diagnoses are secret","B. Functional needs capture who actually needs help and how — across many diagnoses and situations — making planning equitable and practical","C. To avoid treating illness","D. It is only for documentation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A functional lens (e.g., 'cannot self-evacuate,' 'depends on power for a device') groups people by the support they need, which is more actionable than a list of diagnoses.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c10_q10","question":"Which is an example of the 'Transportation' element of CMIST?","options":["A. A patient on home oxygen","B. A person without a vehicle or independent means to evacuate","C. A person who is deaf","D. A person needing a wheelchair"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Transportation covers people who cannot independently evacuate and depend on others or public systems to move to safety.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c10_q11","question":"A person dependent on a power-requiring home ventilator represents which CMIST need?","options":["A. Communication","B. Maintaining health","C. Transportation","D. Independence only"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Maintaining health covers dependence on medications, oxygen, dialysis, and power-dependent medical devices that fail when infrastructure does.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c10_q12","question":"Which is a recognized responder resilience measure?","options":["A. Continuous shifts without breaks","B. Work-rest cycles, buddy systems, leadership support, and post-event follow-up","C. Discouraging any discussion of the event","D. Ignoring signs of burnout"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Sustaining responders requires managed work-rest cycles, peer support, engaged leadership, and follow-up — burnout degrades safety and performance.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c10_q13","question":"Continuity of operations planning primarily ensures:","options":["A. Maximal individual care for one patient","B. Essential services keep running during a disaster and are restored afterward","C. That crisis standards are always used","D. That documentation stops"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Continuity of operations keeps critical functions going and plans their restoration — a bridge between response and recovery.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c10_q14","question":"A disaster response should be considered complete when:","options":["A. The last acute casualty leaves the ED","B. The community and its responders have recovered, with after-action lessons fed back into preparedness","C. The media loses interest","D. The incident commander goes home"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Recovery — rebuilding, chronic-care continuity, behavioral health, and after-action review — extends well past the acute phase and closes the disaster cycle.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c10_q15","question":"Which evacuation-planning failure reflects ignoring vulnerable populations?","options":["A. Providing accessible transport and backup power for device-dependent residents","B. A plan that strands people dependent on dialysis, mobility aids, or transportation","C. Translating alerts into multiple languages","D. Including personal-care attendants in shelter plans"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Plans that overlook access and functional needs leave the most vulnerable behind — precisely what the CMIST framework is designed to prevent.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c10_q16","question":"During a mass-casualty psychological response, a well-meaning volunteer insists survivors each narrate the event in detail 'to process it.' This is:","options":["A. Correct psychological first aid","B. Not part of PFA — forcing trauma recounting can be harmful; PFA provides safety, calm, connection, and linkage instead","C. Required by law","D. The definition of resilience"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Psychological first aid deliberately avoids compelling trauma narration; it focuses on safety, comfort, connectedness, and practical linkage to services.","difficulty":"Hard"}]}},"scenarios":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","cases":[{"id":"c01_s01","title":"Small Town, Big Bus Crash","presentation":"A bus crash outside a small rural town produces 22 injured passengers. The local critical-access hospital has one physician on duty, four nurses, and two ambulances. The nearest trauma center is 90 minutes away.","vitals":{"patients":"22 injured","staff":"1 MD, 4 RNs","transport":"2 ambulances"},"question":"How should this event be classified and managed?","options":["A: A routine emergency — treat patients in order of arrival.","B: A disaster/MCI for this community — needs exceed local resources, so activate the emergency plan, use formal triage, and request mutual aid.","C: Not a disaster because there are fewer than 100 casualties.","D: Wait for a federal declaration before changing procedures."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Twenty-two casualties overwhelm one physician, four nurses, and two ambulances — needs exceed resources, which is the definition of a disaster regardless of absolute numbers. The correct posture is plan activation, triage for the greatest good, and early mutual-aid requests.","clinicalPearl":"Disaster is a local arithmetic problem: the same crash near a level-1 trauma center might be just a busy afternoon."},{"id":"c01_s02","title":"The Plan on the Shelf","presentation":"During accreditation review, a hospital presents a comprehensive 200-page disaster plan. Interviews reveal no staff member has participated in a drill for three years, and the plan's phone tree lists departed employees.","vitals":{"plan":"Comprehensive on paper","exercises":"None in 3 years","contacts":"Outdated"},"question":"What is the most important corrective action?","options":["A: Add more chapters to the plan.","B: Exercise the plan regularly, update contacts, and train staff — planning and practice are inseparable.","C: Nothing — a written plan satisfies preparedness.","D: Replace the plan with verbal instructions."],"correct":1,"explanation":"The PRE-DISASTER Paradigm pairs planning with practice. An unexercised, outdated plan fails under stress; drills reveal gaps (like the dead phone tree) and build the role familiarity a real response requires.","clinicalPearl":"A disaster plan is only as good as its last exercise."},{"id":"c01_s03","title":"The Responder Who Couldn't Respond","presentation":"After an earthquake, a hospital activates its surge plan, but a third of the staff do not report: schools are closed, roads are damaged, and many have no family emergency arrangements. Care capacity collapses despite an intact building.","vitals":{"building":"Intact","staff reporting":"~66%","surge plan":"Activated"},"question":"What preparedness lesson does this illustrate?","options":["A: Surge capacity is only about beds and supplies.","B: Staff personal and family preparedness is a core component of facility surge capacity.","C: Staff who stay home should be dismissed.","D: The surge plan was unnecessary."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Surge capacity = space, supplies, systems, AND staff. Employees without family communication plans, dependent-care arrangements, and go-kits often cannot report, so facility preparedness programs must include personal preparedness.","clinicalPearl":"Beds don't treat patients — people do. Personal preparedness is institutional capacity."}]},"c02":{"chapter":"c02","cases":[{"id":"c02_s01","title":"First on Scene at the Market Explosion","presentation":"You are the first EMS unit at an explosion in a crowded market. Smoke is rising, dozens of people are down or fleeing, and bystanders scream for you to help a bleeding man at your feet.","vitals":{"casualties":"Est. 30+","hazards":"Smoke, unstable stalls, possible 2nd device","resources":"Your unit only"},"question":"What is your correct first sequence of actions?","options":["A: Immediately treat the bleeding man in front of you.","B: Size up and report (detection), establish and announce incident command, address safety/security and hazards — before individual patient care.","C: Drive the nearest casualty to the hospital.","D: Wait outside the area until the police arrive."],"correct":1,"explanation":"The DISASTER Paradigm runs in order: detection (size-up and report), incident command, safety/security, and hazard assessment come before touching the first patient. At a bombing, secondary devices make staging discipline and scene control lifesaving for responders — and effective command saves more victims than one-at-a-time care.","clinicalPearl":"The hardest BDLS skill is stepping past the first casualty to run the checklist — command and safety save more lives than immediate hands-on care."},{"id":"c02_s02","title":"Everyone to Mercy General","presentation":"At a highway pile-up MCI with 25 casualties, transporting crews begin taking every patient to Mercy General, 5 minutes away. Two other hospitals, 15 and 20 minutes away, have received no patients. Mercy's ED calls: they are saturated.","vitals":{"casualties":"25","nearest ED":"Saturated","other EDs":"Idle"},"question":"What has gone wrong, and what should command do?","options":["A: Nothing — nearest hospital is always correct.","B: Evacuation failed: casualties were not distributed. Command should assign destinations by acuity across all appropriate receiving facilities.","C: Mercy General should simply work faster.","D: Stop all transports until Mercy clears."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Sending every casualty to the closest facility relocates the disaster into its ED. The evacuation component requires command-directed distribution: match patient acuity to facility capability and spread the load across the system.","clinicalPearl":"An MCI transported badly becomes a hospital MCI — distribution is a command function, not a driver's choice."},{"id":"c02_s03","title":"The Second Wave","presentation":"Twenty minutes into a response at an industrial fire, crews have settled into patient care. A responder notices a storage tank near the treatment area beginning to vent vapor. The initial hazard assessment had cleared this area.","vitals":{"scene":"Evolving","new hazard":"Venting tank near treatment area","initial assessment":"20 min old"},"question":"What does this development demonstrate?","options":["A: The initial assessment was negligent.","B: Hazard assessment is continuous — scenes evolve, so the treatment area must be relocated and command notified immediately.","C: Vapor clouds are harmless once patients are triaged.","D: Only the safety officer may notice hazards."],"correct":1,"explanation":"The 'Assess hazards' component never ends: an area safe on arrival can become dangerous. Any responder who spots a new hazard reports it at once; command relocates operations and updates the safety perimeter.","clinicalPearl":"Your scene size-up has an expiration time — keep looking up from the patient."}]},"c03":{"chapter":"c03","cases":[{"id":"c03_s01","title":"Two Command Posts","presentation":"At a train derailment with a chemical leak, the fire department has set up a command post on the east side while police run a separate post on the west side. EMS crews receive conflicting orders about staging locations.","vitals":{"agencies":"Fire, Police, EMS, Environmental","command posts":"2 (conflicting)","orders":"Contradictory"},"question":"What is the correct structural fix?","options":["A: Let each agency keep its own command post.","B: Establish unified command — the agencies jointly set objectives at one command post with a single coordinated plan and one Operations section.","C: EMS should create a third command post.","D: Wait for a federal coordinator."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Multi-jurisdiction, multi-discipline incidents call for unified command: shared decision-making, one incident action plan, one Operations section. Parallel command posts guarantee conflicting orders and gaps.","clinicalPearl":"One incident, one plan — unified command merges authority without merging agencies."},{"id":"c03_s02","title":"The Overloaded Supervisor","presentation":"In the hospital's disaster response, the treatment area leader is directly supervising 14 clinicians. Requests are being missed, two patients were nearly given duplicate medications, and the leader cannot say who is assigned where.","vitals":{"direct reports":"14","errors":"Near-misses occurring","tracking":"Lost"},"question":"What ICS principle is violated and what is the fix?","options":["A: Nothing is wrong; busy leaders are normal in disasters.","B: Span of control is broken — subdivide into units of ~5 with unit leaders reporting to the treatment leader.","C: Replace the leader with two co-equal leaders over the same 14 people.","D: Send half the staff home."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Span of control should stay around 3–7 direct reports. The modular fix is subdividing: create unit leaders, each managing a workable group, restoring accountability and safe communication.","clinicalPearl":"When a leader can't name their people, the span has already failed — subdivide before the error happens."},{"id":"c03_s03","title":"Where Do I Go?","presentation":"A hospital activates its incident command for a mass-casualty event. An off-duty nurse hears the news and drives straight to the ED, walking into the treatment area to help without telling anyone.","vitals":{"activation":"HICS active","nurse status":"Not checked in","assignment":"None"},"question":"What should the nurse have done?","options":["A: Exactly what she did — every hand helps.","B: Report to the designated staff check-in/labor pool, receive an assignment and job action sheet, and work under an assigned supervisor.","C: Call the CEO for instructions.","D: Stay home under all circumstances."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Willing staff are valuable only when integrated: check-in establishes accountability, matches skills to needs via job action sheets, and places the responder under one incident supervisor. Untracked helpers break safety and resource management.","clinicalPearl":"In a disaster, checking in IS helping — the labor pool is where good intentions become usable capacity."}]},"c04":{"chapter":"c04","cases":[{"id":"c04_s01","title":"Thirty Down at the Stadium","presentation":"A structural collapse at a stadium exit leaves roughly 30 casualties. You are the designated triage officer. Some victims are screaming, several lie motionless, and dozens of others mill around dazed.","vitals":{"casualties":"~30","your role":"Triage officer","resources":"First units arriving"},"question":"What is your first triage action?","options":["A: Begin detailed head-to-toe exams on the nearest patient.","B: Global sort by voice: ask those who can to walk to a designated area, then ask the rest to wave — assessing the still and obviously bleeding first.","C: Start CPR on the first pulseless casualty.","D: Transport the loudest patient first."],"correct":1,"explanation":"SALT starts with global sorting: walkers are prioritized last, wavers second, and the still or obviously hemorrhaging first. This sorts 30 casualties in seconds and directs individual assessment where it matters most.","clinicalPearl":"Let your voice triage the crowd before your hands triage a patient."},{"id":"c04_s02","title":"The Apneic Adult and the Apneic Child","presentation":"During your assessment pass you find two apneic casualties near each other: a middle-aged man and a 6-year-old girl. You open each airway with positioning. The man remains apneic. After the girl's airway is opened you consider further action.","vitals":{"man":"Apneic after airway opening","child":"Apneic, airway just opened","scene":"Active MCI, resources scarce"},"question":"Per SALT, what is correct?","options":["A: Start CPR on both.","B: The man is Dead (black); for the child, consider two rescue breaths — if breathing resumes she is triaged as living (likely Immediate); if not, she is Dead.","C: Both are Expectant.","D: Tag both Immediate and move on."],"correct":1,"explanation":"In mass-casualty triage, an apneic adult after airway opening is Dead — CPR would consume many rescuers for one arrest. Children get consideration of two rescue breaths because pediatric arrest is typically hypoxic and may reverse with ventilation alone.","clinicalPearl":"SALT's only 'CPR' is two breaths for a child — the highest-yield seconds in pediatric triage."},{"id":"c04_s03","title":"Gray, Not Black","presentation":"A casualty has an open skull injury with exposed brain tissue, agonal-pattern breathing, and no radial pulse. Your only transport is 40 minutes out, and three Immediate patients await treatment. Later, two helicopters and a surgical team arrive.","vitals":{"initial resources":"Minimal","later resources":"2 helicopters + surgical team","patient":"Breathing, catastrophic head injury"},"question":"How is this casualty triaged initially, and what happens when resources improve?","options":["A: Dead initially and finally.","B: Expectant (gray) initially — comfort care, not abandonment; on resource arrival, re-triage and potentially upgrade to Immediate.","C: Immediate initially, Expectant later.","D: Minimal — he is breathing."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Survival is unlikely with the resources initially available, so the casualty is Expectant with comfort care. Expectant is resource-relative: when helicopters and a surgical team arrive, re-triage may upgrade the patient to Immediate.","clinicalPearl":"Expectant is a statement about your resources, not a verdict on the patient — re-triage when the math changes."}]},"c05":{"chapter":"c05","cases":[{"id":"c05_s01","title":"Under the Slab","presentation":"After an earthquake, a 40-year-old man has been pinned across both thighs by a concrete slab for 4 hours. Rescue crews are 10 minutes from lifting the slab. He is alert, in pain, with stable vitals.","vitals":{"hr":"104 bpm","bp":"128/84 mmHg","entrapment":"4 hours, both thighs","extrication":"10 min away"},"question":"What must happen BEFORE the slab is lifted?","options":["A: Nothing — lift immediately, he is stable.","B: Establish IV access and begin aggressive isotonic fluids, with cardiac monitoring ready, anticipating hyperkalemia and hypotension at release.","C: Give potassium supplements for his muscle damage.","D: Apply heat packs to the legs."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Four hours of compression means crush syndrome physiology is loaded and waiting. Pre-release volume expansion and monitoring blunt the reperfusion surge of potassium, myoglobin, and acid — lifting first and treating later risks arrest at the moment of rescue.","clinicalPearl":"In prolonged crush, the rescue itself is the resuscitation event — prepare the patient before you free him."},{"id":"c05_s02","title":"Quiet Apartment, Third Heat Day","presentation":"On day 3 of a heat wave, you find an 82-year-old woman alone in a top-floor apartment with no air conditioning. She is hot to the touch, confused, and mumbling. Skin is flushed and dry.","vitals":{"temp":"41.2 C (106.2 F)","hr":"128 bpm","bp":"96/60 mmHg","loc":"Confused"},"question":"What is the diagnosis and priority?","options":["A: Heat exhaustion — oral fluids and rest.","B: Heat stroke — begin rapid active cooling immediately and continue during transport.","C: Sepsis — antibiotics first.","D: Stroke — thrombolytics."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Severe hyperthermia plus altered mental status is heat stroke. Survival tracks how fast core temperature is lowered: start aggressive active cooling on scene (evaporative/ice packs; immersion where feasible) and keep cooling en route — 'cool first, transport cooling.'","clinicalPearl":"Heat waves kill the isolated elderly quietly at home — and minutes of cooling matter more than minutes of driving."},{"id":"c05_s03","title":"The Second Week Surge","presentation":"Twelve days after a major hurricane, the regional hospital remains 40% over capacity. Today's arrivals include dialysis patients who missed sessions, COPD patients without power for oxygen concentrators, diabetics without insulin refrigeration, and several shelter residents with febrile gastroenteritis.","vitals":{"days post-storm":"12","ED status":"140% capacity","trauma cases":"Few"},"question":"What does this pattern represent and what should planners learn?","options":["A: An unrelated coincidence.","B: The public-health tail — chronic-disease decompensation and shelter outbreaks outlast the trauma phase and must be planned for.","C: Evidence the hurricane response failed.","D: A reason to discharge chronic patients faster."],"correct":1,"explanation":"The medical surge after a natural disaster outlasts the injury surge: interrupted dialysis, oxygen, refrigeration, and medications decompensate chronic disease, while shelters incubate outbreaks. Preparedness must include chronic-care continuity, shelter health services, and multi-week staffing plans.","clinicalPearl":"Storms injure for a day and decompensate for a month — plan the tail, not just the landfall."}]},"c06":{"chapter":"c06","cases":[{"id":"c06_s01","title":"Subway Blast Survivor","presentation":"A bomb detonates in a subway car. A 30-year-old survivor walks out with ringing ears and mild chest tightness. Vitals are initially normal. Ninety minutes later in the treatment area he is dyspneic, tachypneic, and coughing blood-streaked sputum.","vitals":{"initial":"Normal, TM symptoms","90 min":"RR 32, SpO2 88%, hemoptysis","exposure":"Enclosed-space blast"},"question":"What is happening and what caution applies?","options":["A: Anxiety attack — reassure him.","B: Delayed blast lung — give oxygen, escalate care, and if ventilation is needed use the lowest effective pressures, watching for pneumothorax and air embolism.","C: Asthma — bronchodilators only.","D: He was fine initially, so no blast injury is possible."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Enclosed-space blasts multiply primary injury, and blast lung classically declares itself hours later with dyspnea, hypoxia, and hemoptysis. Oxygenate and escalate, but ventilate gently — positive pressure can extend alveolar rupture into pneumothorax or arterial air embolism.","clinicalPearl":"The blast survivor who 'walked away' hasn't finished declaring himself — enclosed-space exposures earn observation."},{"id":"c06_s02","title":"The Second Package","presentation":"A package bomb detonates outside a courthouse, downing several victims. As the first EMS crew arrives, a police officer points out an unattended second backpack 20 meters from the casualties.","vitals":{"casualties":"Visible, some moving","second device":"Suspected, 20 m away","scene":"Uncleared"},"question":"What is the correct EMS action?","options":["A: Rush to the casualties — seconds count.","B: Stage at a safe distance until law enforcement addresses the suspected device; operate under unified command; enter only when directed.","C: Move the backpack away from the casualties.","D: Have bystanders carry the victims to you through the uncleared zone."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Secondary devices are placed to kill responders. EMS stages until the device threat is addressed, integrates with law enforcement under unified command, and enters per the coordinated plan. A blown-up medic rescues no one.","clinicalPearl":"At intentional scenes, the first casualties you protect are your own crew — stage, coordinate, then treat."},{"id":"c06_s03","title":"First Wave at Memorial ED","presentation":"Eight minutes after a marketplace bombing, 30 self-transported patients with lacerations and TM complaints crowd Memorial's ED. The charge physician wants to assign every open bed. You are the hospital incident commander.","vitals":{"arrivals":"30 walking wounded","elapsed":"8 min","EMS units on scene":"Still extricating critical casualties"},"question":"What is the correct capacity decision?","options":["A: Fill all beds now with the walking wounded.","B: Cohort the minor casualties in a fast-track area and hold resuscitation bays and OR capacity for the critical wave arriving by EMS in 30-60 minutes.","C: Close the ED to further arrivals.","D: Send the walking wounded home without assessment."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Bombing arrivals run upside-down: the self-evacuated minor casualties arrive first, and the critical patients — still being extricated — arrive later. Command protects resuscitation capacity for that second wave while safely cohorting and assessing the first.","clinicalPearl":"After a bombing, your first 30 patients are rarely your sickest 30 — plan beds for the wave you haven't met yet."}]},"c07":{"chapter":"c07","cases":[{"id":"c07_s01","title":"Collapse at the Station","presentation":"Dispatch reports multiple people down at a subway platform. Arriving first, you see from the stairwell at least eight casualties — several seizing or twitching, others drooling heavily with constricted pupils. A faint chemical odor drifts up. Commuters are fleeing past you.","vitals":{"casualties":"8+ visible","toxidrome":"Miosis, secretions, twitching","your PPE":"None"},"question":"What is your correct action?","options":["A: Go down to the platform and start triage immediately.","B: Do not enter — stage upwind/uphill, declare a suspected nerve-agent MCI, establish zones, and direct fleeing casualties toward a decon point.","C: Begin CPR on the nearest casualty carried up by bystanders.","D: Ventilate the station by propping doors."],"correct":1,"explanation":"A cluster of collapsing casualties with cholinergic signs is a chemical scene. Unprotected entry adds you to the casualty count. Stage, declare, zone, and channel ambulatory casualties to decon — protected teams extract the rest.","clinicalPearl":"The toxidrome you can see from the stairs is the warning to stay on the stairs."},{"id":"c07_s02","title":"Soaked and Seizing","presentation":"A protected team brings a farm worker from a pesticide tank rupture to the decon corridor. He is soaked in liquid, seizing intermittently, with massive salivation, pinpoint pupils, and audible bronchorrhea.","vitals":{"hr":"48 bpm","rr":"Labored, gurgling","pupils":"Pinpoint","skin":"Liquid-soaked"},"question":"What is the correct management sequence?","options":["A: Transport immediately to the ED as-is.","B: Strip clothing and flush with copious water while giving atropine (titrated to dry secretions) plus pralidoxime via auto-injector and a benzodiazepine for seizures.","C: Give antidotes only — decon can wait until the hospital.","D: Withhold atropine because his heart rate is low."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Liquid organophosphate keeps absorbing through skin, so gross decon (clothes off, copious water) proceeds together with antidotes: atropine titrated until secretions dry (bradycardia is an indication, not a contraindication), pralidoxime to reactivate the enzyme, benzodiazepines for seizures.","clinicalPearl":"In cholinergic poisoning, atropine's endpoint is dry lungs — and a slow heart is a reason to give it, not to hold it."},{"id":"c07_s03","title":"The 'Recovered' Chlorine Worker","presentation":"After a chlorine leak at a pool-supply warehouse, a 35-year-old worker had burning eyes, cough, and throat irritation. After 30 minutes on scene air, he feels 'fine' and wants to go home. Six hours later, similar patients from the same leak begin arriving with severe dyspnea.","vitals":{"initial":"Irritation only, improving","6 h later (cohort)":"Dyspnea, crackles, hypoxia"},"question":"What should have been done with the 'recovered' worker, and why?","options":["A: Discharge on scene — irritant effects are always immediate and complete.","B: Observation with return precautions — pulmonary agents like chlorine and especially phosgene can cause delayed pulmonary edema hours after apparent recovery.","C: Prophylactic antibiotics.","D: Immediate intubation of all exposed."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Choking agents injure the lower airways with a latent period: apparent recovery can precede pulmonary edema by hours. Significant exposures earn observation or, at minimum, explicit return precautions — as the six-hour wave demonstrates.","clinicalPearl":"With chlorine and phosgene, 'feeling fine' is a phase, not an outcome — respect the latent period."}]},"c08":{"chapter":"c08","cases":[{"id":"c08_s01","title":"Three Cities, One Rash","presentation":"Over 24 hours, EDs in three cities several hundred miles apart each report several previously healthy adults with high fever and a progressing vesicular rash that started on the face and hands. None have travel links to each other.","vitals":{"onset":"Synchronous across sites","illness":"Febrile vesicular rash","epi links":"None between cities"},"question":"What should a clinician who recognizes this do?","options":["A: Treat each case locally and wait for lab confirmation before contacting anyone.","B: Immediately notify public health of a possible smallpox/high-consequence event, isolate patients with airborne + contact precautions, and protect staff.","C: Discharge the patients to reduce ED crowding.","D: Assume it is chickenpox and take no special action."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Simultaneous multi-site clusters of an unusual, severe illness are a classic epidemiologic clue. A centrifugal vesicular rash raises smallpox concern — an airborne, high-consequence Category A agent. Early notification, airborne + contact isolation, and staff protection are the pivotal actions; waiting for confirmation squanders the response window.","clinicalPearl":"Three separated clusters at once is the population's way of shouting 'point source' — report before you confirm."},{"id":"c08_s02","title":"Powder in the Mailroom","presentation":"An office reports an envelope leaking white powder; the mailroom worker who opened it is well but frightened. Public health later confirms Bacillus anthracis. Twelve coworkers shared the space.","vitals":{"index worker":"Asymptomatic","exposed coworkers":"12, asymptomatic","agent":"Anthrax (confirmed)"},"question":"What is the appropriate management of the exposed but well coworkers?","options":["A: Isolate them as if they were infectious to others.","B: Post-exposure prophylaxis (antibiotics ± vaccination) through public health, with monitoring — anthrax is not spread person-to-person.","C: No action unless they become ill.","D: Immediate ICU admission for all."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Inhalational anthrax is not transmitted person-to-person, so isolating exposed-but-well contacts is unnecessary; the priority is timely post-exposure prophylaxis (antibiotics, possibly vaccine) dispensed via public health, with monitoring. Prophylaxis is time-sensitive.","clinicalPearl":"Anthrax spreads from the envelope, not from the patient — the intervention for the exposed is prophylaxis, not isolation."},{"id":"c08_s03","title":"Month Two of the Pandemic","presentation":"Two months into a respiratory pandemic, your hospital faces N95 shortages, one-third of staff out sick or caring for family, and ICU demand exceeding ventilator supply. Administrators ask how to sustain the response.","vitals":{"PPE":"N95 shortage","staffing":"~66% available","ICU demand":"Exceeds ventilators"},"question":"Which combination of principles applies?","options":["A: Abandon PPE and treat everyone in the ICU regardless of resources.","B: Protect and conserve the workforce (PPE conservation/extended use, vaccination, mental-health support), expand surge capacity and continuity plans, and prepare crisis standards of care for resource allocation.","C: Close the hospital until supplies arrive.","D: Ignore staffing and focus only on beds."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Prolonged events are won by sustaining the workforce and the system: PPE conservation and vaccination protect staff, surge and continuity plans expand and preserve essential services, and crisis standards of care provide an ethical/legal framework for allocating scarce resources like ventilators.","clinicalPearl":"In a pandemic the scarce resource is often the staff — protect the people and the beds follow."}]},"c09":{"chapter":"c09","cases":[{"id":"c09_s01","title":"Dirty Bomb Downtown","presentation":"An explosion in a plaza injures many people; a detector confirms radioactive contamination scattered by the blast. A critically injured man has an obstructed airway and a bleeding leg wound, and a radiation monitor reads positive over his clothing.","vitals":{"airway":"Obstructed","hemorrhage":"Active leg wound","contamination":"Positive on clothing"},"question":"What is the correct sequence of care?","options":["A: Complete full decontamination before touching him.","B: With standard precautions, manage the airway and control hemorrhage FIRST, then remove clothing (most contamination) and decontaminate.","C: Give potassium iodide and wait.","D: Refuse care because he is contaminated."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Trauma before decon: the airway and bleeding will kill long before external contamination does. Responders use standard precautions, treat the life threats, then remove clothing (which eliminates most contamination) and wash. An RDD's dominant injury is the blast, not radiation.","clinicalPearl":"A dirty bomb is a bombing first and a radiation event second — resuscitate the trauma, then decontaminate."},{"id":"c09_s02","title":"The Frightened Nurse","presentation":"A worker was briefly in a radiation field during an industrial source accident but has no contamination on monitoring. He needs a laceration repaired. A nurse refuses to enter the room, afraid of 'catching radiation.'","vitals":{"contamination survey":"Negative","exposure":"Brief field exposure","injury":"Laceration"},"question":"What is the correct teaching and action?","options":["A: The nurse is right — quarantine the patient for a week.","B: Explain that an irradiated, non-contaminated patient is not radioactive (like after an X-ray) and poses no risk; proceed with normal wound care.","C: Give the patient KI before anyone enters.","D: Transfer the patient to a specialized facility for the laceration."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Exposure is not contamination. With a negative contamination survey, the patient carries no radioactive material and cannot irradiate staff — exactly like a patient who received a diagnostic X-ray. Normal care proceeds; the teaching point calms the team.","clinicalPearl":"You don't 'catch' radiation from an X-ray — and you don't catch it from an irradiated, uncontaminated patient either."},{"id":"c09_s03","title":"Estimating the Dose","presentation":"After a criticality accident, a worker begins vomiting within 20 minutes and has watery diarrhea an hour later. A repeat lymphocyte count shows a sharp drop over several hours.","vitals":{"time to vomiting":"20 min","GI":"Early diarrhea","lymphocytes":"Falling rapidly"},"question":"What do these findings indicate?","options":["A: A trivial exposure — reassure and discharge.","B: A high radiation dose and severe acute radiation syndrome — early vomiting, GI involvement, and a rapid lymphocyte drop predict a poor prognosis; urgent specialized care.","C: Food poisoning unrelated to radiation.","D: Only thyroid injury — give KI and discharge."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Very early vomiting, early GI symptoms, and a rapidly falling lymphocyte count are hallmarks of a high-dose exposure and severe ARS. Time-to-vomiting and lymphocyte kinetics are practical dose/prognosis estimators, and this patient needs urgent specialized management.","clinicalPearl":"The clock and the lymphocyte count are your field dosimeters — the faster the vomiting and the count's fall, the higher the dose."}]},"c10":{"chapter":"c10","cases":[{"id":"c10_s01","title":"Beds Without Nurses","presentation":"During a regional mass-casualty event, a hospital administrator proudly reports 60 newly opened surge beds in a converted conference center. But the nursing supervisor notes there are no additional nurses, the supply room is nearly empty of monitors, and there is no patient-tracking process for the new area.","vitals":{"space":"+60 beds","staff":"None added","stuff":"Monitors short","systems":"No tracking"},"question":"What is the core problem?","options":["A: There is no problem — the beds solve the surge.","B: Only one of the four S's (Space) was addressed; without Staff, Stuff, and Systems, real surge capacity has not increased.","C: The hospital should open even more beds.","D: Crisis standards of care should be declared immediately."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Surge capacity requires all four S's — Staff, Stuff, Space, Systems. Sixty beds without nurses, monitors, or a tracking system is empty capacity. Command must balance the pillars, not just add space.","clinicalPearl":"Counting beds is the easiest and most misleading surge metric — capacity is set by your scarcest S."},{"id":"c10_s02","title":"The Home on the Evacuation List","presentation":"A wildfire evacuation is ordered. On one street live: a man on home dialysis, an elderly woman who is deaf, a wheelchair-dependent veteran with no car, and a family whose child has autism and needs constant supervision. The standard evacuation notice was a single loud siren and an English-language text alert.","vitals":{"dialysis patient":"Power/treatment dependent","deaf resident":"Missed audio alert","wheelchair user":"No transportation","child":"Needs supervision"},"question":"Which framework best guides planning for these residents, and what does it reveal?","options":["A: Triage colors — tag each red/yellow/green.","B: CMIST — Communication (deaf resident, non-English family), Maintaining health (dialysis), Independence (wheelchair), Support/Safety (child), Transportation (no car) — the siren-and-text plan fails all of them.","C: The four S's of surge.","D: Time, distance, shielding."],"correct":1,"explanation":"CMIST organizes access and functional needs: the residents need accessible communication, power/treatment continuity, mobility and transportation assistance, and supervision support. A single audio siren and English text alert reaches none of them — planning to CMIST closes those gaps.","clinicalPearl":"An evacuation plan that assumes everyone can hear, drive, walk, and self-manage leaves the most vulnerable behind — plan to CMIST."},{"id":"c10_s03","title":"The Exhausted Crew","presentation":"Three weeks into a prolonged disaster response, a paramedic supervisor notices her crews are short-tempered, making uncharacteristic errors, sleeping poorly, and one medic quietly says the work feels 'pointless now.' Physical resources are adequate.","vitals":{"duration":"3 weeks","signs":"Irritability, errors, insomnia, hopelessness","physical resources":"Adequate"},"question":"What is happening and what should the supervisor do?","options":["A: Ignore it — responders should be tough.","B: Recognize cumulative stress/burnout and moral distress; implement work-rest cycles, peer/buddy support, leadership check-ins, and access to behavioral-health follow-up.","C: Discipline the medic for negativity.","D: Add more shifts to catch up."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Cumulative stress, moral distress, and burnout degrade judgment, safety, and health over a long response. Resilience measures — managed work-rest cycles, buddy systems, supportive leadership, and behavioral-health follow-up — protect the workforce, which is itself a critical resource. Caring for caregivers is part of the recovery link.","clinicalPearl":"The responders are part of the casualty count over a long event — protecting their minds sustains the whole response."}]}},"algorithms":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","algorithms":[{"id":"c01_alg01","title":"The Disaster Cycle — Health Professional's Role by Phase","description":"The four continuous phases of emergency management and what health professionals contribute in each.","steps":["Mitigation: support measures that reduce future impact — safe facilities, building codes, immunization, community risk reduction.","Preparedness: write and exercise plans, train (BDLS/ADLS), stockpile, prepare yourself and your family.","Response: operate inside incident command using the DISASTER Paradigm — triage, treat, and protect yourself and the scene.","Recovery: restore services, support community and responder mental health, capture lessons learned.","Feed lessons learned back into mitigation and planning — the cycle never ends."]},{"id":"c01_alg02","title":"PRE-DISASTER Readiness Sequence","description":"Pre-event readiness per the PRE-DISASTER Paradigm, from the individual to the community level.","steps":["Plan: personal/family plan, facility plan, community plan — with clear roles.","Practice: drill and exercise the plans; update contacts and supplies after every exercise.","Build resilience: hardened infrastructure, redundant systems, healthy and prepared people.","Educate and train: competency-based courses so all responders share one lexicon.","Re-assess hazards and repeat — readiness decays without maintenance."]}]},"c02":{"chapter":"c02","algorithms":[{"id":"c02_alg01","title":"The DISASTER Paradigm — Response Checklist","description":"The eight ordered components applied by the first-arriving and every subsequent responder at any all-hazards event.","steps":["Detection: size up — do needs exceed resources? Report casualties, hazards, and needs; declare an MCI/disaster if so.","Incident command: the first trained responder establishes and announces command; transfer as senior officers arrive.","Safety and security: protect in order — self, team, public, patients; PPE, staging, perimeter, resource security.","Assess hazards: search for ongoing and secondary hazards (fire, collapse, hazmat, devices); reassess continuously.","Support: request staff, supplies, transport, and special teams early — anticipate the incident an hour ahead.","Triage and treatment: apply SALT; deliver the greatest good for the greatest number.","Evacuation: move the right patient to the right destination; distribute across receiving facilities.","Recovery: begin during response — restore systems, support people, capture lessons learned."]}]},"c03":{"chapter":"c03","algorithms":[{"id":"c03_alg01","title":"Standing Up Incident Command","description":"From first arrival to a fully functioning command structure.","steps":["First trained responder establishes command and announces it on the designated channel.","Perform initial size-up and transmit the detection report.","Appoint command staff as needed: safety officer first, then public information and liaison officers.","Activate functional sections modularly as workload requires: Operations first, then Planning, Logistics, Finance/Administration.","Maintain span of control (~3–7 per supervisor); subdivide with branches/divisions/groups as the incident grows.","Use unified command when multiple jurisdictions/disciplines hold authority.","Transfer command formally with a briefing and announcement when a more qualified/designated officer arrives.","Demobilize modularly as the incident resolves; document through Planning and Finance."]},{"id":"c03_alg02","title":"Health Professional Check-In Flow (Hospital ICS)","description":"How clinical staff enter and work inside the hospital incident command structure.","steps":["On activation, report to the designated check-in point / labor pool — never self-assign.","Receive your incident role and job action sheet.","Identify your single incident supervisor and your reporting channel.","Perform assigned tasks; escalate resource needs and hazards up the chain.","Decline tasks outside your competence and say so — reassignment is a safety function.","At relief or shift end: give a formal handoff and demobilize through the system."]}]},"c04":{"chapter":"c04","algorithms":[{"id":"c04_alg01","title":"SALT Mass-Casualty Triage","description":"The CDC-sponsored national standard triage flow, from global sorting through category assignment.","steps":["STEP 1 — Sort globally: 'If you can hear me and need help, walk to this area' (assess these third). 'Wave your arm or move' (assess these second). Still casualties or obvious life threats: assess FIRST.","STEP 2 — Assess each casualty individually, performing lifesaving interventions that take only seconds:","Control massive hemorrhage (tourniquet/direct pressure).","Open the airway by positioning; for a child, consider 2 rescue breaths.","Needle decompression for tension pneumothorax (trained providers).","Auto-injector antidotes if chemical exposure indicated.","Not breathing after airway opening (adult, or child after breaths) → DEAD (black).","Breathing: ask — obeys commands/purposeful movement? peripheral pulse? no respiratory distress? major hemorrhage controlled?","All YES + minor injuries → MINIMAL (green). All YES + significant injuries → DELAYED (yellow).","Any NO + survivable with current resources → IMMEDIATE (red). Any NO + survival unlikely with current resources → EXPECTANT (gray, comfort care).","Tag/mark, move to the next casualty, and RE-TRIAGE at the treatment area, before transport, and on arrival."]}]},"c05":{"chapter":"c05","algorithms":[{"id":"c05_alg01","title":"Heat Stroke Response","description":"Recognition and cool-first management of environmental heat stroke.","steps":["Suspect heat stroke in any hot-environment patient with altered mental status.","Confirm severe hyperthermia; move the patient out of the heat.","Begin rapid active cooling immediately — ice-water immersion where feasible, otherwise ice packs to neck/axillae/groin plus evaporative cooling.","Manage airway and breathing; check glucose; avoid antipyretics (ineffective for environmental hyperthermia).","Continue cooling during transport ('cool first, transport cooling'); monitor temperature to avoid overshoot.","During heat events, pair clinical response with outreach to isolated, at-risk residents."]},{"id":"c05_alg02","title":"Post-Storm Carbon Monoxide Screen","description":"Detecting the silent post-disaster killer in outage conditions.","steps":["After storms/outages, ask every symptomatic household about generators, charcoal, or heaters used indoors or in attached garages.","Suspect CO with headache, nausea, dizziness, confusion — especially multiple household members or pets affected.","Remove everyone from the environment; give high-flow oxygen.","Transport for evaluation (consider CO-oximetry); alert responders to the source.","Push prevention messaging: generators outdoors, away from windows, with CO alarms."]}]},"c06":{"chapter":"c06","algorithms":[{"id":"c06_alg01","title":"Explosive Event Scene Sequence","description":"Responder priorities at an intentional or suspected-intentional explosion.","steps":["Stage at a safe distance; assume secondary devices until law enforcement clears the scene.","Establish/join unified command with law enforcement and fire.","Enter per the coordinated plan; preserve evidence where care allows.","Apply SALT triage; the dominant lifesaving intervention is hemorrhage control (tourniquets, packing).","Anticipate the casualty pattern: many fragment injuries, occult primary blast injury in survivors near/inside the blast space.","Warn receiving hospitals early and distribute casualties; flag enclosed-space survivors for observation.","Reassess the scene continuously for structural, fire, and device hazards."]},{"id":"c06_alg02","title":"Blast Lung Recognition and Care","description":"Detecting and safely managing primary pulmonary blast injury.","steps":["Suspect in any significant blast exposure — especially enclosed-space — with dyspnea, hypoxia, chest pain, or hemoptysis (may be delayed hours).","Administer high-flow oxygen; monitor SpO2 continuously.","If ventilation is required, use the lowest effective pressures/volumes.","Monitor for tension pneumothorax; decompress if it develops.","Consider arterial air embolism with neuro deficits or sudden collapse.","Observe significant exposures even when initially asymptomatic."]}]},"c07":{"chapter":"c07","algorithms":[{"id":"c07_alg01","title":"Chemical Scene Response Sequence","description":"From detection through decontamination and toxidrome-based care.","steps":["Detect: casualty cluster + one location + similar sudden symptoms (± odors, dead animals) = chemical release.","Stage uphill, upwind, upstream; no unprotected entry; establish hot/warm/cold zones.","Direct ambulatory casualties to the decon corridor; protected teams extract the rest.","Decontaminate: clothing off (removes most contamination), brush dry agents, then copious head-to-toe water.","Triage with SALT; give antidote auto-injectors during lifesaving interventions for the cholinergic toxidrome.","Treat by toxidrome in the cold zone: nerve agent → atropine (titrate to secretions) + pralidoxime + benzodiazepines; cyanide → hydroxocobalamin; pulmonary agents/vesicants → oxygen and supportive care.","Notify hospitals of agent and decon status; intercept self-presenters for decon outside the ED.","Observe exposures with delayed-onset potential (phosgene, chlorine, mustard)."]},{"id":"c07_alg02","title":"Casualty Decontamination Sequence","description":"Gross decontamination in the warm zone.","steps":["Remove casualties from the source; prioritize symptomatic liquid exposures for immediate decon.","Remove all clothing and jewelry — bag and label as contaminated evidence.","Brush off any dry/powdered agent before water.","Flush with copious water head to toe (gentle soap for oily agents); protect airway; mind runoff.","Move the deconned casualty across the line into the cold zone for full assessment and care.","Never allow undeconned casualties or their clothing into clean areas or the ED."]}]},"c08":{"chapter":"c08","algorithms":[{"id":"c08_alg01","title":"Recognizing and Reporting a Biological Event","description":"The clinician-centered detection and initial-response flow for suspected biological events.","steps":["Watch for epidemiologic clues: disease unusual for the area/season, unusually severe/rapidly fatal illness, point-source cluster, unexpected population, unusual exposure route, or simultaneous multi-site outbreaks.","Notify public health immediately — do not wait for laboratory confirmation.","Isolate the ill; apply route-appropriate PPE (contact, droplet, or airborne), defaulting to higher protection if the agent is unknown.","Support public-health measures: quarantine of exposed contacts, post-exposure prophylaxis/vaccination, POD operations, and contact tracing.","Communicate clearly to reduce spread and panic.","Document exposures and cases for surveillance and epidemiologic investigation."]},{"id":"c08_alg02","title":"Pandemic Sustained-Response Priorities","description":"Principles for a prolonged, system-stressing biological event.","steps":["Protect the workforce: PPE (with conservation/extended use when scarce), vaccination, and mental-health support.","Expand surge capacity — space, staff, supplies, and systems.","Maintain continuity of essential clinical and public services.","Apply non-pharmaceutical interventions (distancing, hygiene, masking, isolation/quarantine), especially before vaccines/therapeutics.","Invoke crisis standards of care under legal/ethical frameworks only if demand overwhelms resources.","Plan for sustainable staffing and responder recovery over the long event."]}]},"c09":{"chapter":"c09","algorithms":[{"id":"c09_alg01","title":"Radiological/Nuclear Casualty Management","description":"Responder protection and casualty care at a radiological or nuclear event.","steps":["Protect responders with time, distance, and shielding; wear standard PPE and use radiation monitoring.","Remember PPE prevents contamination but does not stop penetrating gamma radiation — distance and shielding do.","Assess for life-threatening injury: treat airway, breathing, and hemorrhage FIRST, before decontamination.","Decontaminate once stable: remove clothing (most contamination), then wash gently with soap and water from wounds outward.","Address internal contamination via wounds/orifices; consider potassium iodide ONLY for radioiodine exposure.","Estimate severity with time-to-vomiting and lymphocyte-count trends; stage acute radiation syndrome.","Reassure and educate: irradiated (uncontaminated) patients are not a radiation hazard to others; manage worried-well and psychological casualties."]},{"id":"c09_alg02","title":"Distinguishing Exposure From Contamination","description":"The decision that drives responder risk and patient management.","steps":["Ask: was the patient only in a radiation field (irradiation) or is radioactive material present on/in them (contamination)?","Irradiation only, contamination survey negative → patient is NOT radioactive; provide normal care.","External contamination → material on skin/clothing; remove clothing and wash; responders use standard precautions.","Internal contamination → material inhaled/ingested/embedded; manage medically and involve specialists.","In all cases, treat life-threatening injuries before decontamination."]}]},"c10":{"chapter":"c10","algorithms":[{"id":"c10_alg01","title":"Building and Escalating Surge Capacity","description":"Balancing the four S's and moving along the standards-of-care continuum.","steps":["Assess demand against current capacity.","Expand across all four S's together — Staff, Stuff, Space, Systems — recognizing the weakest caps the surge.","Deliver conventional care with normal resources as long as possible.","Shift to contingency care with functionally equivalent adaptations (repurposed space, substituted supplies, adjusted ratios) as demand grows.","If demand overwhelms all adaptations, enter crisis standards of care by formal declaration under an ethical/legal framework.","Continuously address behavioral-health needs and CMIST functional needs.","De-escalate toward conventional care as resources recover; conduct after-action review."]},{"id":"c10_alg02","title":"Psychological First Aid (PFA)","description":"The early, non-intrusive behavioral-health response for survivors and responders.","steps":["Ensure physical safety and meet basic needs (shelter, food, water).","Provide a calm, reassuring presence; reduce arousal.","Connect people with loved ones, accurate information, and each other.","Support self-efficacy — help people take practical next steps.","Foster hope and link individuals to ongoing services.","Do NOT force survivors to recount the traumatic event.","Extend the same care to responders; monitor for cumulative stress and burnout."]}]}},"tables":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","tables":[{"id":"c01_t01","title":"The Four Phases of the Disaster Cycle","headers":["Phase","When","Examples"],"rows":[["Mitigation","Before (ongoing)","Building codes, flood barriers, immunization programs"],["Preparedness","Before","Plans, drills, training, stockpiles, family go-kits"],["Response","During / immediately after","Incident command, triage, treatment, evacuation"],["Recovery","After (weeks to years)","Restoring services, rebuilding, mental-health support, lessons learned"]]},{"id":"c01_t02","title":"Everyday Emergency Care vs Disaster Care","headers":["Aspect","Everyday Care","Disaster Care"],"rows":[["Goal","Maximal care for each patient","Greatest good for the greatest number"],["Resources","Assumed adequate","Explicitly limited; allocated by triage"],["Documentation","Complete records","Abbreviated (triage tags)"],["Roles","Fixed daily roles","Flexible, assigned by incident command"],["Care standard","Conventional","May shift to contingency or crisis standards"]]}]},"c02":{"chapter":"c02","tables":[{"id":"c02_t01","title":"The DISASTER Paradigm at a Glance","headers":["Component","Core Question","Key Actions"],"rows":[["Detection","Do needs exceed resources?","Size up, estimate casualties/hazards, report, declare MCI"],["Incident command","Who is in charge?","Establish, announce, transfer as needed"],["Safety & security","Who must be protected first?","Self → team → public → patients; PPE; perimeter"],["Assess hazards","What can still hurt us?","Ongoing + secondary hazards; continuous reassessment"],["Support","What will we need?","Early requests: staff, supplies, transport, special teams"],["Triage & treatment","Who first, with what?","SALT; greatest good for greatest number"],["Evacuation","Who goes where?","Acuity-matched, distributed destinations"],["Recovery","How do we restore?","Begins during response; systems, people, lessons"]]},{"id":"c02_t02","title":"Obvious vs Insidious Detection","headers":["Feature","Obvious Event","Insidious Event"],"rows":[["Example","Explosion, tornado","Covert biological release, epidemic"],["Signal","Immediate scene chaos","Syndromic clusters across EDs over days"],["Detector","First responders on scene","Clinicians + public-health surveillance"],["Key action","Size-up and MCI declaration","Recognize pattern, notify public health"]]}]},"c03":{"chapter":"c03","tables":[{"id":"c03_t01","title":"The Five ICS Functional Sections","headers":["Section","One-Line Job","Health Examples"],"rows":[["Command","Sets objectives; overall authority (+ safety, PIO, liaison)","Declares surge levels; approves the plan"],["Operations","Does the tactical work","Triage, treatment, transport, decon"],["Planning","Tracks situation/resources; writes the action plan","Bed counts, patient tracking, next operational period"],["Logistics","Gets what the response needs","Ventilators, staff food, radios, supplies"],["Finance/Admin","Tracks costs, claims, time","Emergency procurement, staff hours, reimbursement"]]},{"id":"c03_t02","title":"ICS Core Principles","headers":["Principle","Meaning"],"rows":[["Common terminology","Plain language, no agency codes"],["Modular organization","Activate only what the incident needs; expand/contract"],["Unity of command","Every person reports to exactly one incident supervisor"],["Span of control","~3–7 direct reports per supervisor (optimally ~5)"],["Unified command","Multi-agency incidents share objectives under one plan"],["Accountability","Check-in, assignment, tracking, formal handoffs"]]}]},"c04":{"chapter":"c04","tables":[{"id":"c04_t01","title":"SALT Triage Categories","headers":["Category","Color","Meaning","Action"],"rows":[["Immediate","Red","Life threat, survivable with prompt care","First priority treatment and transport"],["Delayed","Yellow","Significant injuries; care can wait","Treat/transport after Immediate"],["Minimal","Green","Walking wounded, minor injuries","Assess, treat minor issues, monitor for deterioration"],["Expectant","Gray","Alive; survival unlikely with CURRENT resources","Comfort care; re-triage if resources improve"],["Dead","Black","Not breathing after airway opening","No further care; preserve scene/identification"]]},{"id":"c04_t02","title":"SALT Global Sort Priorities","headers":["Response to Commands","Assessment Priority"],"rows":[["Still / obvious life threat","1st — assess first"],["Waves / purposeful movement","2nd"],["Walks to designated area","3rd (last) — still gets assessed"]]},{"id":"c04_t03","title":"Triage-Phase Lifesaving Interventions (Seconds Only)","headers":["Intervention","Indication"],"rows":[["Tourniquet / direct pressure","Massive external hemorrhage"],["Airway positioning","Obstructed airway in an unresponsive casualty"],["2 rescue breaths (child only)","Apneic child after airway opening"],["Needle chest decompression (trained)","Suspected tension pneumothorax"],["Antidote auto-injector","Nerve-agent/organophosphate toxidrome"]]}]},"c05":{"chapter":"c05","tables":[{"id":"c05_t01","title":"Natural Hazard Signatures","headers":["Hazard","Primary Killer","Other Key Injuries/Illness","Responder Hazards"],"rows":[["Hurricane / flood","Drowning (often vehicle-related)","Debris trauma, electrocution, CO poisoning, contaminated wounds, chronic-care collapse","Moving water, downed lines"],["Earthquake","Structural collapse","Crush injury/syndrome, fractures, head injury, dust inhalation","Aftershocks, unstable structures"],["Tornado","Ballistic debris","Penetrating trauma, contaminated wounds, fractures","Damaged structures, blocked access"],["Heat wave","Heat stroke","Chronic-disease decompensation, dehydration","Responder heat stress"],["Cold event","Hypothermia","CO poisoning from improvised heat, house fires, falls","Ice, cold exposure"]]},{"id":"c05_t02","title":"Crush Injury vs Crush Syndrome","headers":["Feature","Crush Injury","Crush Syndrome"],"rows":[["What it is","Local tissue damage from compression","Systemic reperfusion illness after release"],["Timing","During entrapment","At and after extrication"],["Key threats","Fractures, soft-tissue damage, compartment syndrome","Hyperkalemia → dysrhythmia; myoglobinuria → renal failure; shock"],["Critical intervention","Safe extrication","IV fluids BEFORE release; monitoring; renal protection"]]}]},"c06":{"chapter":"c06","tables":[{"id":"c06_t01","title":"The Five Blast Injury Mechanisms","headers":["Class","Mechanism","Typical Injuries"],"rows":[["Primary","Blast pressure wave at air-tissue interfaces","TM rupture, blast lung, GI perforation/hemorrhage, air embolism"],["Secondary","Fragments and debris propelled by the blast","Penetrating trauma — the most common cause of death/injury"],["Tertiary","Body thrown against objects/ground","Blunt trauma, fractures, head injury"],["Quaternary","Everything else from the event","Burns, crush (collapse), smoke inhalation, exacerbated illness"],["Quinary","Device additives","Radiological/chemical/biological contamination ('dirty' additives)"]]},{"id":"c06_t02","title":"Bombing Casualty Flow — Planning Points","headers":["Phase","Who Arrives","Hospital Action"],"rows":[["Minutes 0–15","Self-transported walking wounded (largest group)","Cohort in fast-track; rapid assessment; don't fill resus bays"],["Minutes 30–60+","Critical casualties via EMS after extrication","Protected resuscitation/OR capacity; trauma teams ready"],["Hours","Delayed presenters (blast lung, GI injury, anxiety)","Observation pathways; return precautions for discharged"]]}]},"c07":{"chapter":"c07","tables":[{"id":"c07_t01","title":"Chemical Agent Classes","headers":["Class","Examples","Presentation","Key Treatment"],"rows":[["Nerve agents / organophosphates","Sarin, VX, pesticides","Cholinergic toxidrome: SLUDGE/DUMBELS, miosis, twitching, seizures, apnea","Decon; atropine (titrate to secretions) + pralidoxime; benzodiazepines"],["Vesicants (blister)","Mustard, lewisite","Skin/eye/airway blistering; mustard effects DELAYED hours","Decon; supportive care (no antidote for mustard)"],["Pulmonary / choking","Chlorine, phosgene","Airway irritation → pulmonary edema; phosgene classically delayed","Remove from exposure; oxygen; observation; supportive"],["Asphyxiants","Cyanide, CO","Rapid collapse, seizures, arrest; SpO2 may look normal","Hydroxocobalamin (cyanide); high-flow O2"],["Riot-control","CS, OC (pepper)","Intense eye/skin/airway irritation, usually self-limited","Fresh air; irrigation; supportive"]]},{"id":"c07_t02","title":"Scene Zones at a Hazmat/Chemical Event","headers":["Zone","What It Is","Who Works There"],"rows":[["Hot","Contamination present","Only teams with hazard-appropriate PPE"],["Warm","Decontamination corridor","Decon teams in appropriate PPE"],["Cold","Clean support and treatment area","Unprotected clinical providers, command, staging"]]},{"id":"c07_t03","title":"Cholinergic Toxidrome Mnemonics","headers":["Mnemonic","Stands For"],"rows":[["SLUDGE","Salivation, Lacrimation, Urination, Defecation, GI distress, Emesis"],["DUMBELS","Defecation, Urination, Miosis, Bronchorrhea/Bronchospasm, Emesis, Lacrimation, Salivation"],["Killer B's","Bronchorrhea, Bronchospasm, Bradycardia"]]}]},"c08":{"chapter":"c08","tables":[{"id":"c08_t01","title":"CDC Bioterrorism Agent Categories","headers":["Category","Characteristics","Examples"],"rows":[["A (highest priority)","Easily disseminated/transmitted, high mortality, public-health impact","Anthrax, botulism, plague, smallpox, tularemia, viral hemorrhagic fevers"],["B","Moderately easy to disseminate, moderate morbidity, lower mortality","Q fever, brucellosis, ricin, food/water-safety threats"],["C","Emerging pathogens that could be engineered for mass spread","Emerging infectious diseases (e.g., novel viruses)"]]},{"id":"c08_t02","title":"Isolation Precautions by Transmission Route","headers":["Precaution","PPE / Setting","Example Agents"],"rows":[["Standard","Hand hygiene, gloves/PPE per task","All patients, always"],["Contact","Gown and gloves","Agents spread by touch/contaminated surfaces"],["Droplet","Surgical mask within close range","Pneumonic plague, influenza"],["Airborne","N95+ respirator, negative-pressure room","Smallpox, tuberculosis, measles"]]},{"id":"c08_t03","title":"Isolation vs Quarantine vs Prophylaxis","headers":["Tool","Applies To","Purpose"],"rows":[["Isolation","People who are ill","Prevent them from infecting others"],["Quarantine","Exposed but not yet ill","Watch and contain in case they become infectious"],["Post-exposure prophylaxis","Exposed but well","Prevent disease from developing (antibiotics/vaccine)"]]}]},"c09":{"chapter":"c09","tables":[{"id":"c09_t01","title":"Irradiation vs External vs Internal Contamination","headers":["Type","What It Means","Risk to Others","Management"],"rows":[["Irradiation (exposure)","Was in a radiation field (like an X-ray)","None — patient not radioactive","Normal care; reassurance"],["External contamination","Radioactive material on skin/clothing","Can spread to responders/surfaces","Remove clothing, wash; standard precautions"],["Internal contamination","Material inhaled/ingested/in wounds","Minimal to others; medical concern for patient","Medical management; specialist involvement; KI if radioiodine"]]},{"id":"c09_t02","title":"Responder Radiation Protection: Time, Distance, Shielding","headers":["Principle","How It Works","Practical Action"],"rows":[["Time","Dose accumulates with exposure duration","Work efficiently; rotate responders; minimize time near source"],["Distance","Dose falls with the inverse square of distance","Step back; keep the maximum practical distance from the source"],["Shielding","Mass absorbs radiation","Use walls, vehicles, or earth between you and the source"]]},{"id":"c09_t03","title":"Acute Radiation Syndrome by Increasing Dose","headers":["Sub-syndrome","System","Features"],"rows":[["Prodrome","Whole body","Nausea/vomiting; earlier onset = higher dose"],["Hematopoietic","Bone marrow","Falling blood counts → infection, bleeding (lowest ARS doses)"],["Gastrointestinal","GI tract","Severe diarrhea, fluid/electrolyte loss (higher dose)"],["Cardiovascular/CNS","Heart/brain","Rapid collapse; usually fatal (highest dose)"]]}]},"c10":{"chapter":"c10","tables":[{"id":"c10_t01","title":"The Four S's of Surge Capacity","headers":["Pillar","Includes","Failure Example"],"rows":[["Staff","Clinical + support personnel, callback, credentialed volunteers","Beds open but no one to staff them"],["Stuff","Supplies, medications, equipment, PPE","Ventilators unavailable for ICU surge"],["Space","Beds, alternate care sites, treatment areas","No room to place incoming casualties"],["Systems","Command, communications, tracking, policies","No patient tracking or coordination"]]},{"id":"c10_t02","title":"Standards of Care Continuum","headers":["Level","Resources","Care Delivered"],"rows":[["Conventional","Normal","Usual standard of care"],["Contingency","Adapted but functionally equivalent","Repurposed space, substituted supplies, adjusted staffing"],["Crisis","Overwhelmed despite adaptation","Formally declared allocation of scarce resources for population benefit"]]},{"id":"c10_t03","title":"CMIST Functional-Needs Framework","headers":["Element","Population Need","Example"],"rows":[["Communication","Access to alerts and information","Deaf/limited-English/blind residents"],["Maintaining health","Ongoing medical dependence","Medications, oxygen, dialysis, powered devices"],["Independence","Assistive equipment/support to function","Wheelchairs, assistive devices, personal-care attendants"],["Support/Safety/Self-determination","Supervision and support","Some cognitive/psychiatric conditions; children"],["Transportation","Means to evacuate","People without independent transport"]]}]}}};
